irus pandemic in France]] \n*[[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Netherlands]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.info-coronavirus.be/en/ www.info-coronavirus.be], information website from the Belgian government\n*[https://epidemio.wiv-isp.be/ID/Pages/2019-nCoV.aspx New Coronavirus (Disease: COVID-19, Virus: SARS-CoV-2)], [[Sciensano]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Belgium]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Europe|Belgium]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Belgium]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:2020 in Belgium|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "Jona", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGraphs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Belgium"}
{"title_page": "Keith Flint", "text_new": "{{short description|English dancer and vocalist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Keith Flint\n| image           = Keith_in_2009.jpg\n| caption         = Flint in 2009\n| image_size      = 220px\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date|1969|09|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Redbridge, London]], England\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|df=y|2019|03|04|1969|09|17}}\n| death_place     = [[North End, Essex]], England\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Dance music|Dance]]|[[techno]]|[[punk rock]]}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|dancer|motorcycle racer}}\n| years_active    = 1990\u20132019\n| label            =\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[The Prodigy]]| [[Flint (band)|Flint]]}}\n[[File:Flintsignature.png|180px]]\n}}\n'''Keith Charles Flint''' (17 September 1969 \u2013 4 March 2019) was an English singer, dancer and motorcycle racer. He was a founding member of the [[Electronic dance music|electronic dance]] act [[the Prodigy]]. Starting out as a dancer, he became the frontman of the group and performed on the group's two UK number one singles, \"[[Firestarter (The Prodigy song)|Firestarter]]\" and \"[[Breathe (The Prodigy song)|Breathe]]\" both released in 1996. He was also the lead singer of his own band, [[Flint (band)|Flint]]. He owned a motorcycle racing team, Team Traction Control, which won four [[Isle of Man TT]] races across 2015 and 2016, and competed in the [[British Superbike Championship|British Supersport Championship]].\n\n==Early life==\nFlint was born in [[Redbridge, London]], to Clive and Yvonne Flint, on 17 September 1969.<ref>England & Wales, Birth Index: 1916\u20132005, September 1969, vol. 5d, p. 2989</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprodigy.info/members/keith-flint.html|title=Keith Flint \u2013 The Prodigy.info|website=theprodigy.info}}</ref> Clive Flint was the son of a German Jewish immigrant and worked as an engineering consultant.<ref name=\":2\" /> Keith Flint  was initially raised in East London but in the mid-1970s his parents moved out to a quiet suburban [[Cul de sac|cul-de-sac]] in [[Springfield, Essex|Springfield]], [[Essex]]. His childhood was described as [[Dysfunctional family|unhappy and he feuded with his parents]], who parted when he was young.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47442312 |title= The Prodigy's Keith Flint dies aged 49 |website= BBC News |first= Mark |last=Savage |date= 4 March 2019 |access-date= 4 March 2019}}</ref> He attended the [[Boswells School]] in [[Chelmsford]] and moved to [[Braintree, Essex|Braintree]] after leaving school.<ref>{{cite web |title=Keith Flint biography |url=https://theprodigy.info/members/keith-flint.html |website=The Prodigy |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Flint was described as being a \"bright boy with [[dyslexia]]\" and was disruptive in class. He was expelled from school at the age of 15. Flint then worked as a [[roofer]] and later enthusiastically embraced the [[acid house]] scene of the late 1980s.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /> Musically, Flint was a childhood fan of [[the Jam]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/04/keith-flint-obituary|title=Keith Flint obituary|last=Sweeting|first=Adam|date=4 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=12 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and in the late 1980s he listened to bands like [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/03/05/keith-flint-the-prodigy-obituary-essay|title=Keith Flint took the rockstar fairy tale and gave it devil hair|last=Haynes|first=Gavin|date=5 March 2019|publisher=Thefader.com|accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\n[[File:Flint&Holiday.jpg|thumb|Flint with Prodigy guitarist [[Rob Holliday]]]]\nFlint met [[Disc jockey|DJ]] [[Liam Howlett]] at local rave club the Barn in Braintree and said he liked Howlett's taste in music.{{sfn|Roach|2010|p=22}} After receiving a mixtape from Howlett, Flint came back with great enthusiasm, insisting that Howlett should be playing his tracks up on stage and that Flint, along with friend [[Leeroy Thornhill]], would dance to them.{{sfn|Roach|2010|p=23}} Flint, Howlett and Thornhill were joined by MC [[Maxim (musician)|Maxim Reality]] and became a successful electronic dance act called the Prodigy.\n\nIn 1996, just prior to the release of the Prodigy's third album, Flint moved from being a dancer for the group to being its frontman when he performed vocals on the hit single \"[[Firestarter (The Prodigy song)|Firestarter]]\" and the accompanying video showcasing Flint's new and soon-to-be iconic [[punk rock|punk]] look.<ref name=\"Roberts\">Roberts, David (2006). [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]. London: Guinness World Records Limited.</ref> This trend continued with the next Prodigy single \"[[Breathe (The Prodigy song)|Breathe]]\", on which Flint sang lead vocals, with [[Maxim (musician)|Maxim]] backing him up.<ref name=\"GUAR\">{{cite news |last1=Beaumont-Thomas |first1=Ben |title=Keith Flint: Prodigy singer dies aged 49 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/04/prodigy-singer-keith-flint-dies-aged-49 |access-date=4 March 2019 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe 1997 album ''[[The Fat of the Land]]'' featured Flint's vocal contributions to several tracks, namely \"Breathe\", \"Serial Thrilla\", \"Fuel My Fire\" and \"Firestarter\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Comeau |first1=Dave |title=Best Keith Flint Prodigy songs as fans pay tribute following singer's sudden death |url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/best-keith-flint-prodigy-songs-15917832 |access-date=4 March 2019 |publisher=Surrey Live |date=4 March 2019}}</ref> In 2002, the single \"[[Baby's Got a Temper]]\" was released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Prodigy single \"Tempered\" by radio |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-prodigy-143-1378275 |website=NME |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Flint did not perform vocals on the next Prodigy album, ''[[Always Outnumbered, Never Outgunned]]'' (2004), although he did appear on the \"Hotride \u2013 El Batori Mix\", on the \"[[Hotride]]\" single.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Prodigy \u2013 \"Hotride\" | url=https://www.discogs.com/The-Prodigy-Hotride-EP/release/342192 |website=discogs.org |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Prodigy album ''[[Invaders Must Die]]'' was released on 23 February 2009 and featured vocals by Flint on multiple tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/invaders-must-die-mw0000813114|title=Invaders Must Die|publisher=AllMusic|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Flint released a single titled \"War\" with dubstep artist [[Caspa]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=War|publisher=Virgin Records|id=VST2050|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nFlint experimented with solo projects, including his [[punk rock]] bands [[Flint (band)|Flint]], remixes by Steven \u201cStitch\u201d Held at The Recovery Room and Clever Brains Fryin'. Flint's debut album, ''Device #1'', was cancelled before its release, leaving \"Aim4\" as their only single to be commercially released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/prodigy/news/keith-flint-glad-his-solo-career-flopped_4669281|title=Keith Flint Glad His Solo Career Flopped|work=Contact Music|date=9 April 2015|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Motorcycle racing==\nFlint was a keen [[Motorcycling|motorcyclist]]. He rode 2,400&nbsp;km (1,500 miles) from England to southern Spain to attend the [[2007 Spanish motorcycle Grand Prix]] and also raced in club competitions. He rode with [[Lee Thompson (saxophonist)|Lee Thompson]] of the band [[Madness (band)|Madness]]. He had his own motorcycle team, Team Traction Control, which competed in the [[British Supersport Championship]] as part of the [[British Superbike Championship]] before stepping up to the British Superbike Championship in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/motorcycling/great-guy-who-loved-his-racing-motorcycle-tributes-to-prodigy-singer-and-team-traction-control-owner-keith-flint-37876121.html |title=Great guy who loved his racing: Motorcycle tributes to Prodigy singer and Team Traction Control owner Keith Flint |work=The Belfast Telegraph |date=4 March 2019 |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> In 2015 Team Traction Control machines won two [[Isle of Man TT]] races, ridden by [[Ian Hutchinson (motorcyclist)|Ian Hutchinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iomtt.com/news/2015/12/07/keith-flint-ttc-ian%20hutchinson-tt-2016|title=Keith Flint confirms Hutchinson Ride For TT in 2016|work=Isle of Man TT|date=7 December 2015|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> The team and [[Ian Hutchinson (motorcyclist)|Ian Hutchinson]] repeated their two victories again in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iomtt.com/news/2016/06/08/supersport-report-ian-hutchinson-equals-hailwoods-wins |title=Ian Hutchinson Wins Supersport 2 To Equal Hailwood |work=Isle of Man TT Official website |date=8 June 2016 |access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFlint dated television presenter [[Gail Porter]]; the couple split in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/aug/03/celebrity.gailporter |title='Babies look at me and stop crying. It's like I'm one of them' |work=The Guardian |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 2006, Flint married Japanese DJ Mayumi Kai who performed as DJ Gedo Super Mega Bitch.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/prodigy-singer-flint-to-wed-289169.html|title=Prodigy singer Flint to wed|last=|first=|date=13 December 2006|work=Irish Examiner|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/japanese-dj-mayumi-kai-denies-keith-flints-wife-confusion-spouse-name-2457773|title=Japanese DJ Mayumi Kai denies she was married to Keith Flint amid confusion over wife with same name|last=|first=|date=6 March 2019|work=NME|access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> The couple were reported to be separated at the time of Flint's death.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/keith-flint-obituary-3502qkmwx|title=Keith Flint obituary|date=4 March 2019|work=The Times|access-date=9 March 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nFlint had a [[tattoo]] across his stomach of the word \"Inflicted\", a reference to a lyric in \"Firestarter\".<ref name=\":2\" /> Flint was notoriously difficult on transatlantic flights; on one occasion he had to be restrained from kicking down the door to the cockpit.<ref name=\":2\" /> Prior to his marriage Flint suffered from depression and an addiction to prescription painkillers.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /><ref name=\"GUAR\" /> Flint kept fit by [[boxing]] and practising [[Jujutsu|jiu-jitsu]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2014, he bought and renovated the Leather Bottle pub in [[Pleshey]], Essex and became a popular landlord.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/interview-essex-band-prodigy-ahead-new-album/story-26243048-detail/story.html|title=Interview with Essex band The Prodigy for new album release The Day Is My Enemy|date=27 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402031645/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Interview-Essex-band-Prodigy-ahead-new-album/story-26243048-detail/story.html|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> Flint kept a [[Swear jar|jar]] in which customers were required to put a pound if they made a \"firestarter\" joke as he lit the pub's fire.<ref name=\":2\" /> He ended his connection with the pub without explanation in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essexlive.news/the-prodigy-s-keith-flint-quits-the-leather-bottle-pub-in-pleshey-after-ruffling-feathers/story-30226338-detail/story.html|title=The Prodigy's Keith Flint quits running pub near Chelmsford|first=Clare|last=Youell|date=24 March 2017|work=Essex Live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nFlint lived in a [[Listed building|listed]] Tudor [[manor house]] near [[Great Dunmow|Dunmow]], Essex.<ref name=\":3\" /> He had a small [[Track racing|flat track]] in his back garden, where he rode some of his motorcycles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorcyclenews.com/news/2019/march/keith-flint-motorbikes/|title=Keith Flint: My life in bikes|date=4 March 2019|website=Motorcycle News|language=en|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.motoheadmag.com/rip-keith-flint-the-dirt-bike-fan/|title=RIP Keith Flint: The dirt bike fan|date=4 March 2019|website=MotoHead|language=en-GB|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref> Flint was a lover of animals and was an enthusiastic [[twitcher]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He built a pond in his garden to attract birds and kept several dogs and horses at his home.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/features/keith-flint-1969-2019-nme-obituary-2456861|title=Keith Flint, 1969\u20132019: the twisted face of rave, the beating heart of The Prodigy|last=Stubbs|first=Dan|date=6 March 2019|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nFlint's final public performance with the Prodigy was on 5 February 2019 at Trusts Arena in [[Auckland]], New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.setlist.fm/setlist/the-prodigy/2019/the-trusts-arena-auckland-new-zealand-139535cd.html|title=The Prodigy Setlist at The Trusts Arena, Auckland|website=setlist.fm|language=en|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref> On Saturday 2 March 2019, Flint took part in the Chelmsford [[Parkrun]], for the third consecutive week, in which he achieved his personal best time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/keith-flint-the-prodigy-storming-chelmsford-parkrun-personal-best-2456961|title=The Prodigy's Keith Flint had just achieved a \"storming\" Parkrun personal best|last=Moore|first=Sam|date=4 March 2019|website=NME|language=en-GB|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2019, just after 8:10 am, [[Essex Police]] were called to Flint's home in [[North End, Essex|North End]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/04/prodigy-singer-keith-flint-dies-aged-49|title=Keith Flint: Prodigy vocalist dies aged 49|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|date=4 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> near [[Great Dunmow]], Essex, in response to concerns for his welfare.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/keith-flint-dead-prodigy-cause-age-firestarter-a8806456.html|title=The Prodigy frontman Keith Flint dead aged 49|date=4 March 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref> Flint was pronounced dead at the scene, and the police did not treat the death as suspicious. It was later confirmed at an inquest into his death he had died as a result of hanging. The coroner adjourned the inquest until 23 July for a full hearing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-47523338|title=Keith Flint: Prodigy singer died from hanging|date=11 March 2019|accessdate=11 March 2019|website=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nLater that day, bandmate Liam Howlett stated in an Instagram post that Flint had taken his own life.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /><ref name=\"GUAR\" /> The official band website then went black with an announcement of his death<ref>{{cite web|title=The Prodigy |website=The Prodigy |url=https://theprodigy.com |access-date=5 March 2019 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76e6HxPTr |archivedate=5 March 2019}}</ref> and the Prodigy announced that they had cancelled all forthcoming shows.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Prodigy |website=The Prodigy |url=https://twitter.com/the_prodigy/status/1103022371462623232?s=09 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> It was later revealed by [[Emily Eavis]] that this included a booking at the 2019 [[Glastonbury Festival]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The next scheduled Prodigy performance was to be the [[Est\u00e9reo Picnic Festival]] on 6 April 2019 in [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/feed/107821/|title=Est\u00e9reo Picnic brings The Prodigy to Colombia for the first time|date=27 December 2018|website=Resident Advisor|language=en|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, many musical artists and music industry figures from around the world paid tribute to Flint.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nme.com/news/music/my-heart-is-broken-for-him-sex-pistols-icon-johnny-rotten-pays-tribute-to-keith-flint-2457740 |title= \"My heart is broken for him\": Sex Pistols icon Johnny Rotten pays tribute to Keith Flint |work= NME |author= Nick Reilly |date=4 March 2019|access-date=6 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|url=https://twitter.com/petetong/status/1102607464174968834 |number=1102607464174968834 |title=Sad to wake up to the news that we lost Keith Flint, a true original. The Prodigy have made a huge contribution to dance culture and electronic music around the world. Keith\u2019s contribution as the band\u2019s iconic front man was immense and he will be dearly missed R.I.P xx |date=4 March 2019|user=petetong|language=en|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/05/stars-pay-tribute-to-keith-flint-prodigy |title= Stars pay tribute to Keith Flint: 'A powerhouse of energy and attitude' |work= The Guardian |author= Laura Snapes |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Mark Savage\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47456948 |title= Keith Flint: Stars and fans recall the Firestarter's soft side |work= BBC News |author= Mark Savage |date=4 March 2019|access-date=4 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> Many tributes highlighted Flint's gentle temperament, illustrating a personal kindness, politeness and generosity that contrasted with his energetic and sometimes aggressive stage persona.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Mark Savage\"/>\n\nFlint's funeral was held on 29 March 2019.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/29/prodigy-fans-from-around-world-gather-for-keith-flint-funeral|title=Prodigy fans from around world gather for Keith Flint's funeral|date=29 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> There was a 1.5 mile public procession attended by fans from around the world followed by a private ceremony at St Mary's Church [[Bocking, Essex|Bocking]], Essex attended by family and friends<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-47753446|website=BBC News|title=Fans 'raise roof' at Keith Flint funeral|date=29 March 2019|access-date=29 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> including Flint's wife, Mayumi Kai, and bandmates Liam Howlett, Maxim, and Leeroy Thornhill.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIt was established by the coroners inquest on 8 May 2019 that there was insufficient evidence to conclude a suicide verdict in relation to Flint's death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/may/08/keith-flint-inquest-not-enough-evidence-for-suicide-verdict-coroner-rules|title=Keith Flint: not enough evidence for suicide verdict, coroner rules|last=Association|first=Press|date=8 May 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 May 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Legacy ===\nAfter Flint's death, fans used the hashtag 'Firestarter4Number1' on social media in a campaign to try to get the song \"Firestarter\" to Number 1 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] as a mark of respect for Flint and to raise awareness for [[male suicide|male]] [[Suicide in the United Kingdom|suicide in the UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/kerrang/entertainment/music/the-prodigy-for-number-one/|title=Prodigy fans launch 'Firestarter for Number 1' campaign in memory of Keith Flint|last1=Colothan|first1=Scott|website=Kerrang! Radio|publisher=Planet Radio|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, fashion designer [[Donatella Versace]] dedicated her spring/summer 2020 menswear show in [[Milan]] to Keith Flint's memory.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2019/jun/17/donatella-versace-pays-homage-to-the-prodigy-keith-flint-in-milan|title=Donatella Versace pays homage to the Prodigy's Keith Flint in Milan|last=Conlon|first=Scarlett|date=2019-06-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Versace, who was a friend of Flint's, dressed male models in clothing reflecting his style and they sported Flint's distinctive fire starter hair style.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nWhilst performing at Glastonbury Festival in June 2019, [[Liam Gallagher]] dedicated \"[[Champagne Supernova]]\" to Flint.<ref>https://www.nme.com/news/music/liam-gallagher-dedicates-champagne-supernova-keith-flint-glastonbury-set-2519417</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===With the Prodigy===\n{{main|The Prodigy discography}}\n* ''[[Experience_(The_Prodigy_album)|Experience]]'' (1992) <small>(Credited as band member; does not perform)</small>\n* ''[[Music for the Jilted Generation]]'' (1994) <small>(Credited as band member; does not perform)</small>\n* ''[[The Fat of the Land]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Their Law: The Singles 1990\u20132005]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Invaders Must Die]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[World's on Fire (album)|World's on Fire]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Day Is My Enemy]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[No Tourists]]'' (2018)\n\n===With Flint===\n*''[[Flint (band)#Albums|Device #1]]'' (2003)<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.discogs.com/Keith-Flint-Prodigy-Album-Device-1/release/2532975| title = Flint + The Prodigy| publisher = [[Discogs]] | access-date = 4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Other sources===\n* {{cite book|last=James|first=Martin|title=The \"Prodigy\"|year=2002|publisher=Sanctuary Publishing Ltd. |edition=Paperback|isbn=978-1-860-74356-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Roach|first=Martin|title=The Prodigy: The Official Story&nbsp;\u2013 Electronic Punks|year=2010 |publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=978-1-784-18964-8|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs artist}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47456948 Keith Flint: Stars and fans recall the Firestarter's soft side]. BBC News. Published 5 March 2019.\n\n{{The Prodigy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flint, Keith}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Big beat musicians]]\n[[Category:Breakbeat hardcore musicians]]\n[[Category:British techno musicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths by hanging]]\n[[Category:Deaths in East of England]]\n[[Category:English electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:English male dancers]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:English people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English punk rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Hardcore techno musicians]]\n[[Category:Kerrang! Awards winners]]\n[[Category:People from Braintree, Essex]]\n[[Category:People from Great Dunmow]]\n[[Category:People from Ilford]]\n[[Category:People from the City of Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:Singers from Essex]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:The Prodigy members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English dancer and vocalist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name            = Keith Flint\n| image           = Keith_in_2009.jpg\n| caption         = Flint in 2009\n| image_size      = 220px\n| background      = solo_singer\n| birth_date      = {{Birth date|1969|09|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Redbridge, London]], England\n| death_date      = {{Death date and age|df=y|2019|03|04|1969|09|17}}\n| death_place     = [[North End, Essex]], England\n| genre           = {{hlist|[[Dance music|Dance]]|[[techno]]|[[punk rock]]}}\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|dancer|motorcycle racer}}\n| years_active    = 1990\u20132019\n| label            =\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[The Prodigy]]| [[Flint (band)|Flint]]}}\n[[File:Flintsignature.png|180px]]\n}}\n'''Keith Charles Flint''' (17 September 1969 \u2013 4 March 2019) was an English singer, dancer and motorcycle racer. He was a founding member of the [[Electronic dance music|electronic dance]] act [[the Prodigy]]. Starting out as a dancer, he became the frontman of the group and performed on the group's two UK number one singles, \"[[Firestarter (The Prodigy song)|Firestarter]]\" and \"[[Breathe (The Prodigy song)|Breathe]]\" both released in 1996. He was also the lead singer of his own band, [[Flint (band)|Flint]]. He owned a motorcycle racing team, Team Traction Control, which won four [[Isle of Man TT]] races across 2015 and 2016, and competed in the [[British Superbike Championship|British Supersport Championship]].\n\n==Early life==\nFlint was born in [[Redbridge, London]], to Clive and Yvonne Flint, on 17 September 1969.<ref>England & Wales, Birth Index: 1916\u20132005, September 1969, vol. 5d, p. 2989</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://theprodigy.info/members/keith-flint.html|title=Keith Flint \u2013 The Prodigy.info|website=theprodigy.info}}</ref> Clive Flint was the son of a German Jewish immigrant and worked as an engineering consultant.<ref name=\":2\" /> Keith Flint  was initially raised in East London but in the mid-1970s his parents moved out to a quiet suburban [[Cul de sac|cul-de-sac]] in [[Springfield, Essex|Springfield]], [[Essex]]. His childhood was described as [[Dysfunctional family|unhappy and he feuded with his parents]], who parted when he was young.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47442312 |title= The Prodigy's Keith Flint dies aged 49 |website= BBC News |first= Mark |last=Savage |date= 4 March 2019 |access-date= 4 March 2019}}</ref> He attended the [[Boswells School]] in [[Chelmsford]] and moved to [[Braintree, Essex|Braintree]] after leaving school.<ref>{{cite web |title=Keith Flint biography |url=https://theprodigy.info/members/keith-flint.html |website=The Prodigy |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Flint was described as being a \"bright boy with [[dyslexia]]\" and was disruptive in class. He was expelled from school at the age of 15. Flint then worked as a [[roofer]] and later enthusiastically embraced the [[acid house]] scene of the late 1980s.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /> Musically, Flint was a childhood fan of [[the Jam]]<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/04/keith-flint-obituary|title=Keith Flint obituary|last=Sweeting|first=Adam|date=4 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=12 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> and in the late 1980s he listened to bands like [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/03/05/keith-flint-the-prodigy-obituary-essay|title=Keith Flint took the rockstar fairy tale and gave it devil hair|last=Haynes|first=Gavin|date=5 March 2019|publisher=Thefader.com|accessdate=25 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\n[[File:Flint&Holiday.jpg|thumb|Flint with Prodigy guitarist [[Rob Holliday]]]]\nFlint met [[Disc jockey|DJ]] [[Liam Howlett]] at local rave club the Barn in Braintree and said he liked Howlett's taste in music.{{sfn|Roach|2010|p=22}} After receiving a mixtape from Howlett, Flint came back with great enthusiasm, insisting that Howlett should be playing his tracks up on stage and that Flint, along with friend [[Leeroy Thornhill]], would dance to them.{{sfn|Roach|2010|p=23}} Flint, Howlett and Thornhill were joined by MC [[Maxim (musician)|Maxim Reality]] and became a successful electronic dance act called the Prodigy.\n\nIn 1996, just prior to the release of the Prodigy's third album, Flint moved from being a dancer for the group to being its frontman when he performed vocals on the hit single \"[[Firestarter (The Prodigy song)|Firestarter]]\" and the accompanying video showcasing Flint's new and soon-to-be iconic [[punk rock|punk]] look.<ref name=\"Roberts\">Roberts, David (2006). [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]. London: Guinness World Records Limited.</ref> This trend continued with the next Prodigy single \"[[Breathe (The Prodigy song)|Breathe]]\", on which Flint sang lead vocals, with [[Maxim (musician)|Maxim]] backing him up.<ref name=\"GUAR\">{{cite news |last1=Beaumont-Thomas |first1=Ben |title=Keith Flint: Prodigy singer dies aged 49 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/04/prodigy-singer-keith-flint-dies-aged-49 |access-date=4 March 2019 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe 1997 album ''[[The Fat of the Land]]'' featured Flint's vocal contributions to several tracks, namely \"Breathe\", \"Serial Thrilla\", \"Fuel My Fire\" and \"Firestarter\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Comeau |first1=Dave |title=Best Keith Flint Prodigy songs as fans pay tribute following singer's sudden death |url=https://www.getsurrey.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/best-keith-flint-prodigy-songs-15917832 |access-date=4 March 2019 |publisher=Surrey Live |date=4 March 2019}}</ref> In 2002, the single \"[[Baby's Got a Temper]]\" was released.<ref>{{cite web |title=Prodigy single \"Tempered\" by radio |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/the-prodigy-143-1378275 |website=NME |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Flint did not perform vocals on the next Prodigy album, ''[[Always Outnumbered, Never Outgunned]]'' (2004), although he did appear on the \"Hotride \u2013 El Batori Mix\", on the \"[[Hotride]]\" single.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Prodigy \u2013 \"Hotride\" | url=https://www.discogs.com/The-Prodigy-Hotride-EP/release/342192 |website=discogs.org |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Prodigy album ''[[Invaders Must Die]]'' was released on 23 February 2009 and featured vocals by Flint on multiple tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/invaders-must-die-mw0000813114|title=Invaders Must Die|publisher=AllMusic|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> Flint released a single titled \"War\" with dubstep artist [[Caspa]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title=War|publisher=Virgin Records|id=VST2050|year=2012}}</ref>\n\nFlint experimented with solo projects, including his [[punk rock]] bands [[Flint (band)|Flint]], remixes by Steven \u201cStitch\u201d Held at The Recovery Room and Clever Brains Fryin'. Flint's debut album, ''Device #1'', was cancelled before its release, leaving \"Aim4\" as their only single to be commercially released.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/prodigy/news/keith-flint-glad-his-solo-career-flopped_4669281|title=Keith Flint Glad His Solo Career Flopped|work=Contact Music|date=9 April 2015|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Motorcycle racing==\nFlint was a keen [[Motorcycling|motorcyclist]]. He rode 2,400&nbsp;km (1,500 miles) from England to southern Spain to attend the [[2007 Spanish motorcycle Grand Prix]] and also raced in club competitions. He rode with [[Lee Thompson (saxophonist)|Lee Thompson]] of the band [[Madness (band)|Madness]]. He had his own motorcycle team, Team Traction Control, which competed in the [[British Supersport Championship]] as part of the [[British Superbike Championship]] before stepping up to the British Superbike Championship in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/sport/motorcycling/great-guy-who-loved-his-racing-motorcycle-tributes-to-prodigy-singer-and-team-traction-control-owner-keith-flint-37876121.html |title=Great guy who loved his racing: Motorcycle tributes to Prodigy singer and Team Traction Control owner Keith Flint |work=The Belfast Telegraph |date=4 March 2019 |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> In 2015 Team Traction Control machines won two [[Isle of Man TT]] races, ridden by [[Ian Hutchinson (motorcyclist)|Ian Hutchinson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iomtt.com/news/2015/12/07/keith-flint-ttc-ian%20hutchinson-tt-2016|title=Keith Flint confirms Hutchinson Ride For TT in 2016|work=Isle of Man TT|date=7 December 2015|access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref> The team and [[Ian Hutchinson (motorcyclist)|Ian Hutchinson]] repeated their two victories again in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.iomtt.com/news/2016/06/08/supersport-report-ian-hutchinson-equals-hailwoods-wins |title=Ian Hutchinson Wins Supersport 2 To Equal Hailwood |work=Isle of Man TT Official website |date=8 June 2016 |access-date=17 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFlint dated television presenter [[Gail Porter]]; the couple split in 2001.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2008/aug/03/celebrity.gailporter |title='Babies look at me and stop crying. It's like I'm one of them' |work=The Guardian |access-date=4 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 2006, Flint married Japanese DJ Mayumi Kai who performed as DJ Gedo Super Mega Bitch.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/entertainment/prodigy-singer-flint-to-wed-289169.html|title=Prodigy singer Flint to wed|last=|first=|date=13 December 2006|work=Irish Examiner|access-date=1 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/japanese-dj-mayumi-kai-denies-keith-flints-wife-confusion-spouse-name-2457773|title=Japanese DJ Mayumi Kai denies she was married to Keith Flint amid confusion over wife with same name|last=|first=|date=6 March 2019|work=NME|access-date=8 March 2019}}</ref> The couple were reported to be separated at the time of Flint's death.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/keith-flint-obituary-3502qkmwx|title=Keith Flint obituary|date=4 March 2019|work=The Times|access-date=9 March 2019|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nFlint had a [[tattoo]] across his stomach of the word \"Inflicted\", a reference to a lyric in \"Firestarter\".<ref name=\":2\" /> Flint was notoriously difficult on transatlantic flights; on one occasion he had to be restrained from kicking down the door to the cockpit.<ref name=\":2\" /> Prior to his marriage Flint suffered from depression and an addiction to prescription painkillers.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /><ref name=\"GUAR\" /> Flint kept fit by [[boxing]] and practising [[Jujutsu|jiu-jitsu]].<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nIn 2014, he bought and renovated the Leather Bottle pub in [[Pleshey]], Essex and became a popular landlord.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/interview-essex-band-prodigy-ahead-new-album/story-26243048-detail/story.html|title=Interview with Essex band The Prodigy for new album release The Day Is My Enemy|date=27 March 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402031645/http://www.hertsandessexobserver.co.uk/Interview-Essex-band-Prodigy-ahead-new-album/story-26243048-detail/story.html|archivedate=2 April 2015}}</ref> Flint kept a [[Swear jar|jar]] in which customers were required to put a pound if they made a \"firestarter\" joke as he lit the pub's fire.<ref name=\":2\" /> He ended his connection with the pub without explanation in 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.essexlive.news/the-prodigy-s-keith-flint-quits-the-leather-bottle-pub-in-pleshey-after-ruffling-feathers/story-30226338-detail/story.html|title=The Prodigy's Keith Flint quits running pub near Chelmsford|first=Clare|last=Youell|date=24 March 2017|work=Essex Live}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" />\n\nFlint lived in a [[Listed building|listed]] Tudor [[manor house]] near [[Great Dunmow|Dunmow]], Essex.<ref name=\":3\" /> He had a small [[Track racing|flat track]] in his back garden, where he rode some of his motorcycles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.motorcyclenews.com/news/2019/march/keith-flint-motorbikes/|title=Keith Flint: My life in bikes|date=4 March 2019|website=Motorcycle News|language=en|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.motoheadmag.com/rip-keith-flint-the-dirt-bike-fan/|title=RIP Keith Flint: The dirt bike fan|date=4 March 2019|website=MotoHead|language=en-GB|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref> Flint was a lover of animals and was an enthusiastic [[twitcher]].<ref name=\":2\" /> He built a pond in his garden to attract birds and kept several dogs and horses at his home.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/features/keith-flint-1969-2019-nme-obituary-2456861|title=Keith Flint, 1969\u20132019: the twisted face of rave, the beating heart of The Prodigy|last=Stubbs|first=Dan|date=6 March 2019|website=NME|language=en-US|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nFlint's final public performance with the Prodigy was on 5 February 2019 at Trusts Arena in [[Auckland]], New Zealand.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.setlist.fm/setlist/the-prodigy/2019/the-trusts-arena-auckland-new-zealand-139535cd.html|title=The Prodigy Setlist at The Trusts Arena, Auckland|website=setlist.fm|language=en|access-date=9 March 2019}}</ref> On Saturday 2 March 2019, Flint took part in the Chelmsford [[Parkrun]], for the third consecutive week, in which he achieved his personal best time.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/keith-flint-the-prodigy-storming-chelmsford-parkrun-personal-best-2456961|title=The Prodigy's Keith Flint had just achieved a \"storming\" Parkrun personal best|last=Moore|first=Sam|date=4 March 2019|website=NME|language=en-GB|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 4 March 2019, just after 8:10 am, [[Essex Police]] were called to Flint's home in [[North End, Essex|North End]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/04/prodigy-singer-keith-flint-dies-aged-49|title=Keith Flint: Prodigy vocalist dies aged 49|last=Beaumont-Thomas|first=Ben|date=4 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> near [[Great Dunmow]], Essex, in response to concerns for his welfare.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/keith-flint-dead-prodigy-cause-age-firestarter-a8806456.html|title=The Prodigy frontman Keith Flint dead aged 49|date=4 March 2019|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref> Flint was pronounced dead at the scene, and the police did not treat the death as suspicious. It was later confirmed at an inquest into his death he had died as a result of hanging. The coroner adjourned the inquest until 23 July for a full hearing.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-essex-47523338|title=Keith Flint: Prodigy singer died from hanging|date=11 March 2019|accessdate=11 March 2019|website=bbc.co.uk}}</ref>\n\nLater that day, bandmate Liam Howlett stated in an Instagram post that Flint had taken his own life.<ref name=\"BBCSavage\" /><ref name=\"GUAR\" /> The official band website then went black with an announcement of his death<ref>{{cite web|title=The Prodigy |website=The Prodigy |url=https://theprodigy.com |access-date=5 March 2019 |archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/76e6HxPTr |archivedate=5 March 2019}}</ref> and the Prodigy announced that they had cancelled all forthcoming shows.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Prodigy |website=The Prodigy |url=https://twitter.com/the_prodigy/status/1103022371462623232?s=09 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref> It was later revealed by [[Emily Eavis]] that this included a booking at the 2019 [[Glastonbury Festival]].<ref name=\":0\" /> The next scheduled Prodigy performance was to be the [[Est\u00e9reo Picnic Festival]] on 6 April 2019 in [[Bogot\u00e1]], [[Colombia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.residentadvisor.net/feed/107821/|title=Est\u00e9reo Picnic brings The Prodigy to Colombia for the first time|date=27 December 2018|website=Resident Advisor|language=en|access-date=9 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nFollowing his death, many musical artists and music industry figures from around the world paid tribute to Flint.<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.nme.com/news/music/my-heart-is-broken-for-him-sex-pistols-icon-johnny-rotten-pays-tribute-to-keith-flint-2457740 |title= \"My heart is broken for him\": Sex Pistols icon Johnny Rotten pays tribute to Keith Flint |work= NME |author= Nick Reilly |date=4 March 2019|access-date=6 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite tweet|url=https://twitter.com/petetong/status/1102607464174968834 |number=1102607464174968834 |title=Sad to wake up to the news that we lost Keith Flint, a true original. The Prodigy have made a huge contribution to dance culture and electronic music around the world. Keith\u2019s contribution as the band\u2019s iconic front man was immense and he will be dearly missed R.I.P xx |date=4 March 2019|user=petetong|language=en|access-date=10 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite news |url= https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/05/stars-pay-tribute-to-keith-flint-prodigy |title= Stars pay tribute to Keith Flint: 'A powerhouse of energy and attitude' |work= The Guardian |author= Laura Snapes |date=5 March 2019 |access-date=6 March 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Mark Savage\">{{cite news |url= https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47456948 |title= Keith Flint: Stars and fans recall the Firestarter's soft side |work= BBC News |author= Mark Savage |date=4 March 2019|access-date=4 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> Many tributes highlighted Flint's gentle temperament, illustrating a personal kindness, politeness and generosity that contrasted with his energetic and sometimes aggressive stage persona.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\"Mark Savage\"/>\n\nFlint's funeral was held on 29 March 2019.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/mar/29/prodigy-fans-from-around-world-gather-for-keith-flint-funeral|title=Prodigy fans from around world gather for Keith Flint's funeral|date=29 March 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=29 March 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> There was a 1.5 mile public procession attended by fans from around the world followed by a private ceremony at St Mary's Church [[Bocking, Essex|Bocking]], Essex attended by family and friends<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-essex-47753446|website=BBC News|title=Fans 'raise roof' at Keith Flint funeral|date=29 March 2019|access-date=29 March 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> including Flint's wife, Mayumi Kai, and bandmates Liam Howlett, Maxim and Leeroy Thornhill.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nIt was established by the coroners inquest on 8 May 2019 that there was insufficient evidence to conclude a suicide verdict in relation to Flint's death.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/may/08/keith-flint-inquest-not-enough-evidence-for-suicide-verdict-coroner-rules|title=Keith Flint: not enough evidence for suicide verdict, coroner rules|last=Association|first=Press|date=8 May 2019|work=The Guardian|access-date=8 May 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n=== Legacy ===\nAfter Flint's death, fans used the hashtag 'Firestarter4Number1' on social media in a campaign to try to get the song \"Firestarter\" to Number 1 in the [[UK Singles Chart]] as a mark of respect for Flint and to raise awareness for [[male suicide|male]] [[Suicide in the United Kingdom|suicide in the UK]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://planetradio.co.uk/kerrang/entertainment/music/the-prodigy-for-number-one/|title=Prodigy fans launch 'Firestarter for Number 1' campaign in memory of Keith Flint|last1=Colothan|first1=Scott|website=Kerrang! Radio|publisher=Planet Radio|access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, fashion designer [[Donatella Versace]] dedicated her spring/summer 2020 menswear show in [[Milan]] to Keith Flint's memory.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2019/jun/17/donatella-versace-pays-homage-to-the-prodigy-keith-flint-in-milan|title=Donatella Versace pays homage to the Prodigy's Keith Flint in Milan|last=Conlon|first=Scarlett|date=2019-06-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-06-17|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Versace, who was a friend of Flint's, dressed male models in clothing reflecting his style and they sported Flint's distinctive fire starter hair style.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nWhilst performing at Glastonbury Festival in June 2019, [[Liam Gallagher]] dedicated \"[[Champagne Supernova]]\" to Flint.<ref>https://www.nme.com/news/music/liam-gallagher-dedicates-champagne-supernova-keith-flint-glastonbury-set-2519417</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===With the Prodigy===\n{{main|The Prodigy discography}}\n* ''[[Experience_(The_Prodigy_album)|Experience]]'' (1992) <small>(Credited as band member; does not perform)</small>\n* ''[[Music for the Jilted Generation]]'' (1994) <small>(Credited as band member; does not perform)</small>\n* ''[[The Fat of the Land]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[Their Law: The Singles 1990\u20132005]]'' (2005)\n* ''[[Invaders Must Die]]'' (2009)\n* ''[[World's on Fire (album)|World's on Fire]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[The Day Is My Enemy]]'' (2015)\n* ''[[No Tourists]]'' (2018)\n\n===With Flint===\n*''[[Flint (band)#Albums|Device #1]]'' (2003)<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.discogs.com/Keith-Flint-Prodigy-Album-Device-1/release/2532975| title = Flint + The Prodigy| publisher = [[Discogs]] | access-date = 4 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Other sources===\n* {{cite book|last=James|first=Martin|title=The \"Prodigy\"|year=2002|publisher=Sanctuary Publishing Ltd. |edition=Paperback|isbn=978-1-860-74356-6|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|last=Roach|first=Martin|title=The Prodigy: The Official Story&nbsp;\u2013 Electronic Punks|year=2010 |publisher=John Blake Publishing|isbn=978-1-784-18964-8|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs artist}}\n*{{IMDb name}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-47456948 Keith Flint: Stars and fans recall the Firestarter's soft side]. BBC News. Published 5 March 2019.\n\n{{The Prodigy}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flint, Keith}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Big beat musicians]]\n[[Category:Breakbeat hardcore musicians]]\n[[Category:British techno musicians]]\n[[Category:Deaths by hanging]]\n[[Category:Deaths in East of England]]\n[[Category:English electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:English male dancers]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English motorcycle racers]]\n[[Category:English people of German-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:English punk rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Hardcore techno musicians]]\n[[Category:Kerrang! Awards winners]]\n[[Category:People from Braintree, Essex]]\n[[Category:People from Great Dunmow]]\n[[Category:People from Ilford]]\n[[Category:People from the City of Chelmsford]]\n[[Category:Singers from Essex]]\n[[Category:Singers from London]]\n[[Category:The Prodigy members]]\n", "name_user": "Anaesthete", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDeath", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keith_Flint"}
{"title_page": "Thompson/Center Arms", "text_new": "{{short description|Firearms manufacturer}}\n{{About|Thompson/Center Arms|the unrelated Thompson submachinegun|Thompson submachinegun}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Thompson/Center Arms Inc\n| logo             = TC Logo S&W sm.png\n| logo_size        = 250px\n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| genre            = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 1965\n| founder          = K. W. Thompson Tool & Warren Center\n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n| location_country = [[U.S.]]\n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Firearms]]\n| products         = [[rifle]]s, [[pistols]]\n| services         = \n| market cap       = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            =\n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = [[Smith & Wesson]]\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = http://www.tcarms.com/\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Thompson/Center Arms''' is an American firearms company based in Springfield, Massachusetts. The company is best known for its line of interchangeable-barrel, single-shot pistols and rifles. Thompson/Center also manufactures [[muzzle-loading]] rifles and is credited with creating the resurgence of their use in the 1970s.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1960s, Warren Center developed an unusual break-action, single-shot pistol in his basement workshop that later became known as the Contender. Meanwhile, the K.W. Thompson Tool Company had been searching for a product to manufacture year-round. In 1965, Warren Center joined the K.W. Thompson Tool Company, and together, they announced Warren Center's Contender pistol in 1967. Although it sold for more than comparable hunting revolvers, the flexibility of being able to shoot multiple calibers by simply changing out the barrel and sights and its higher accuracy soon made it popular with handgun hunters.<ref name=\"Zwoll\">{{cite book | last = Van Zwoll | first = Wayne| title = Hunter's Guide to Long-Range Shooting | publisher = Stackpole Books| year = 2006| location = | page = 332 | isbn = }}</ref> As K.W. Thompson Tool began marketing Center's Contender pistol, the company name was changed to Thompson/Center Arms Company. Then, in 1970, Thompson/Center created the modern black powder industry, introducing Warren Center's Hawken-styled black powder muzzle-loader rifle.<ref name=\"CS1\">{{cite book | last = Stephens | first = Charles| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Thompson/Center Contender Pistol: How To Tune, Time, Load, And Shoot For Accuracy | publisher = Paladin Press| year = 1996| location = Boulder, CO | pages = 64 | isbn = 978-0-87364-885-1 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2007, Thompson/Center was purchased by [[Smith & Wesson]].<ref>[http://ir.smith-wesson.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=90977&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=942841&highlight 13009 - Smith&Wesson: Press Releases<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2010, Smith & Wesson announced that the original Rochester, New Hampshire plant would be closed and manufacturing was transferred to Springfield, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20101210/GJNEWS_01/712109872/0/SEARCH|title=In Rochester: Thompson/Center Arms plant to close|first=Jake| last=O'Donnell|date= December 10, 2010|publisher=Fosters Daily Democrat}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the closure of Thompson/Center arms in Rochester, New Hampshire, Thompson Investment Casting opened in the same town continuing production of metal products for various companies including Smith & Wesson.\n\n==Break-action pistols==\nThompson/Center's success came with the emergence of long range [[handgun hunting]], target shooting, and, especially, [[metallic silhouette shooting]].<ref name=\"Layne\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.shootingtimes.com/ammo/ammunition_st_magseven_200902/ |last=Simpson |first=Layne |title=The Contender's Magnificent 7 |journal=Shooting Times |volume=2009 |issue=2 |date=January 4, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160921095258/http://www.shootingtimes.com/ammo/ammunition_st_magseven_200902/ |archivedate=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=September 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Their [[break-action]], [[single-shot]] design brought [[rifle]]-like accuracy and power in a handgun, which was a new concept at the time. Originally designed only for interchangeable barrels in [[.38 Special]] and [[.22 LR]], subsequent handgun developments by Thompson/Center led to a wider range of interchangeable barrels for use with many more cartridges. Opening and closing the break-open action is accomplished by squeezing the outside bottom of the trigger guard toward the grip/buttstock, at which time the action opens, and an extractor manually extracts the cartridge.\n\n===Contender===\n{{Main|Thompson/Center Contender}}\n[[File:TC-Contender.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Contender in 45 Colt/.410 with ventilated rib]]\nThe Contender, first introduced in 1967, is a break-action, single-shot pistol or rifle with a number of unique features. The first unique feature is the way the barrel is attached to the frame. By removing the fore-end, a large hinge pin is exposed; by pushing this hinge pin out, the barrel can be removed. Since the sights and extractor remain attached to the barrel in the Contender design, the frame itself contains no cartridge-specific features. A barrel of another caliber can be installed and pinned in place, the fore-end replaced, and the pistol is ready to shoot with a different barrel and pre-aligned sights. This allowed easy changes of calibers, sights, and barrel lengths, with only a flat screwdriver being required for change-out.<ref name=\"Ayoob2012\">{{cite book |last=Ayoob |first=Massad |authorlink=Massad Ayoob |title=Massad Ayoob's Greatest Handguns of the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JYmgHFwqT2gC&pg=PA266 |date=May 29, 2012 |publisher=F+W Media |isbn=978-1-4402-2877-3 |pages=241\u2013266 |chapter=Thompson Center Single Shots}}</ref>\n\n===The Encore===\nThe Encore was released in 1983. The Encore uses a different trigger mechanism, designed to be stronger than the original Contender's and to make the break-action easier to open. The Encore uses a considerably larger and stronger frame than the Contender, and accordingly, is found in over 86 cartridges - ranging from [[.22 Hornet]] to the huge [[.416 Rigby]]. There has even been one pistol-length stainless barrel made in .600 Nitro Express. The Encore barrel list also includes shotgun barrels in 28, 20, and 12 gauge, and muzzleloading barrels in .45, .50 caliber, and 12 gauge using #209 shotgun primers. In 2007, Encore rimfire barrels became available in 22 LR and 17 HMR, featuring a unique monoblock design that required no alteration to the frame assembly.\n\nAn upgraded Encore is called the Pro Hunter which generally includes stocks with rubber \"Flex Tech\" inserts and are stainless or carbon steel with weather shielding. There are other slight differences among the rifles including the breech plug on muzzleloader versions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcarms.com/firearms/interchangeable-platforms/encore-pro-hunter/platform |publisher=T/C Arms |title=Interchangeable Platforms |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131213062307/http://www.tcarms.com/firearms/interchangeable-platforms/encore-pro-hunter/platform |archivedate=December 13, 2013 |accessdate=September 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===The Contender G2===\nThe original Contender, now known as the generation one (G1) Contender, was replaced by the G2 Contender soon after the Encore came out. The G2 Contender is essentially dimensionally the same as the original Contender, but uses an Encore style trigger group. Due to the changes in the trigger mechanism, and to differences in the angle of the grip relative to the boreline of the gun, the buttstocks and pistol grips are different between the G1 and G2 Contenders and will not interchange. The G2, though, uses essentially the same barrels and fore-ends as the original Contender{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}<!-- Dead link, no archive, no alternate source found beyond the other cited source <ref>http://tcarms.com/TC_IMAGES/TC_Catalog_2006/TC2006_Pg46-47.pdf</ref>--> and barrels will interchange, with the only two exceptions being the G2 muzzleloading barrels, which will only fit the G2 frame, and the Herrett barrels/fore-ends, which are specific for use only on a G1 frame.<ref name=\"Potts\">{{cite journal |last=Potts |first=Bruce |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Thompson Center G2 Contender Rifle Review |journal=Shooting Times |volume=2008 |issue=10 |pages= |publisher= |date=October 1, 2008 |url= | doi= |id= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nUnlike the original Contender, dry-firing of the G2 Contender is possible only in the center (safe) hammer position, located on the hammer between the centerfire and rimfire positions. Also, unlike the original Contender, the break-action does not need to be opened/closed (cycled) to practice dry-firing, provided the hammer is lowered between dry firing \"shots\". The adjustability of G2 Contender triggers is also slightly different from the original G1 Contender.\n\n===General legalities===\n\nThe receiver on a Contender, whether G1 or G2, is the portion of the combined grip/buttstock assembly containing the trigger mechanism, and this is legally considered the serial-numbered gun. Hence, barrels with iron or telescopic sights, and even the hinge pin, are all simply gun parts, with no serial numbers, making the choice of changing cartridges from a multitude of rimfire, centerfire rifle and pistol cartridges, and even shotgun shells, very simple.\n\nIt is possible to fit a shoulder stock on a pistol frame in place of a pistol grip, and, when combined with a 16\" or longer barrel (see \"Thompson/Center Arms and the Supreme Court\" below), a Contender may be legally converted from a pistol to a rifle or reversed. Although it is technically possible to fit a pistol grip on an original Contender rifle frame, and use a pistol barrel to convert it from being a rifle to a pistol, this is not legal in the USA, being an illegal creation of a pistol from a rifle. In order to be able to go back and forth, the receiver must have been originally sold as a pistol, per [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] rules.\n\n====California Legalities====\n\nSee [[Gun laws in California]]\n*Possession of a Thompson/Center Arms .45/.410 pistol barrel is illegal in California, for both dealers and individuals, and such a barrel may not legally be shipped into the state, or even taken into California for a hunting trip, by reason of it being classified as a short barreled shotgun (SBSG) when used with a Contender receiver.<ref>{{cite web |title=California Dangerous Weapons Control Law ARTICLE 2. UNLAWFUL CARRYING AND POSSESSION OF WEAPONS 12020 |publisher=State of California |year=2008 |url=http://ag.ca.gov/firearms/dwcl/12020.php |accessdate=January 29, 2013 |quote=As used in this section, a \"short-barreled shotgun\" means any of the following: (A) A firearm which is designed or redesigned to fire a fixed shotgun shell and having a barrel or barrels of less than 18 inches in length. (B) A firearm which has an overall length of less than 26 inches and which is designed or redesigned to fire a fixed shotgun shell.}}</ref>\n\n==Muzzleloading rifles==\n[[File:TC-Hawken.JPG|thumb|right|400px|TC Hawken percussion rifle]]\n \nThompson/Center manufactures a variety of [[Muzzleloader|muzzleloading]] rifles of both traditional and inline designs, and sells percussion and flintlock rifles in a wide variety of bore diameters. Some of the better-known models are the Renegade, the [[Hawken rifle|Hawken]], the Big Boar, and the White Mountain.\n\nThe traditional Thompson/Center muzzleloaders are largely responsible for the resurgence of black powder hunting that began in the U.S. in 1970 when Warren Center designed the firm's Hawken-styled rifle. Thompson/Center's reintroduced Hawken-styled rifle with solid brass hardware and an American walnut stock, styled in large part on \"plains rifles\" made by Hawken in the 1800s, has become one of the most-copied firearms designs in history.<ref>{{cite journal | last =Towsley | first = Bryce| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Mighty Hawken| journal = Hunting Magazine| volume = 15| issue = 6| pages = | publisher =Petersen | year = 2003| url = | doi = | id = | accessdate = }}</ref> Thompson/Center produced these rifles in the following models and calibers:\n\n'''Cherokee:'''\nBarrel: 24\u201d octagonal, twist: 1:30 (32) & 1:48 (36 & 45),\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 32, 36 & 45,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 1994,\nIgnition: percussion\n\n'''Seneca:'''\nBarrel: 27\u201d octagonal, twist: 1:30 (32) & 1:48 (36 & 45),\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 32, 36 & 45,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 1987,\nIgnition: percussion\n\n'''Hawken:'''\nBarrel: 28\u201d octagonal, twist: 1:48, except 1:66 on 50 cal deep button rifling,\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 45, 50 & 54,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: 45 & 54 discontinued, 50 in production, many special editions,\nIgnition: flint & percussion\n\n'''Cougar:'''\nSpecial edition of the '''Hawken''', satin finish barrel, stainless furniture, highly figured wood\n\n'''Renegade:'''\nBarrel: 26\u201d octagonal, 1:38 (50), 1:48 (50 & 54), 1: 66 (50 deep button rifling), smoothbore (56),\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 50, 54 & 56, \nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued,\nIgnition: flintlock & percussion\n\n'''Big Boar:'''\nBarrel: 26\u201d octagonal, 1:48,\nTrigger: single,\nCaliber: 58,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued,\nIgnition: percussion\n\n'''Encore 209x50:''' \nA modern design muzzleloader that can interchange with centerfire barrels. Based on a single-shot, break-action, the 209x50 is capable of \"[[minute of Angle|minute of angle]]\" accuracy. The 209x50 can handle charges of up to {{convert|150|gr|g}} of black powder or Pyrodex equivalent. Using a 26\" barrel and a {{convert|250|gr|g|adj=on}} bullet with 3 Pyrodex Pellets, it produces a muzzle velocity of 2203&nbsp;ft./second.\n\n'''G2 Contender:''' \nA modern design muzzleloader which accepts magnum charges for long range shooting. Charges of up to {{convert|150|gr|g}} of FFG Black Powder or three (3) 50-grain Pyrodex Pellets produce velocities of approximately {{convert|2400|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}} at the muzzle. The Omega can handle {{convert|150|gr|g}} of Black Powder or Pyrodex equivalent, or three {{convert|50|gr|g|adj=on}} Pyrodex pellets. With its 28\" barrel it burns magnum charges very efficiently.\n\n'''Triumph:'''\nThis T/C muzzleloader comes in .50 cal. with a 28\" barrel and composite stock.\n\n==Muzzleloading pistols==\n[[File:Thompson Center Patriot Pistol.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Thompson/Center Patriot Black Powder Muzzleloader Pistol chambered in .45.]]\n[[File:Thompson Center Scout Pistol.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Thompson/Center Scout Black Powder Muzzleloader Pistol chambered in .54.]]\n\n'''Patriot:'''\nBarrel: 9\u201d octagonal,\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: .36 & .45,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 1997,\nIgnition: percussion.\n\n'''Scout:'''\nBarrel: 15\u201d round,\nTrigger: single set,\nCaliber: 45, 50 & 54,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 199?,\nIgnition: percussion.\n\nA major factory fire at the Thompson/Center factory in 1996 destroyed all tooling and parts for the Scout and Patriot pistols and the Seneca rifle. As a result they were discontinued for sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20121207/column10/112079770 |title=Outdoors: Thompson/Center Arms spirit lives on |date=December 7, 2012 |author=Mark Blazis |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160921094143/http://www.telegram.com/article/20121207/column10/112079770 |archivedate=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=September 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Bolt action rifles==\n[[File:TC Venture Predator.jpg|thumb|A T/C Venture Predator in Real Tree camouflage]]\n'''Compass'''<br>\nBarrel: 22\", 24\"<br>\nTrigger: Single stage, adjustable<br>\nCaliber: [[.204 Ruger]], [[.22-250 Remington]], [[.223 Remington]], [[.243 Winchester]], [[.270 Winchester]], [[.280 Remington]], [[.300 Winchester Short Magnum]], [[.300 Winchester Magnum]], [[.308 Winchester]], [[6.5mm Creedmoor]], [[.30-06 Springfield]], [[7mm Remington Magnum]], and [[7mm-08 Remington]]<br>\nStock: Polymer<br>\nStatus: In production\n\n'''Venture'''<br>\nBarrel: 22\", 24\"<br>\nTrigger: Single stage, adjustable<br>\nCaliber: [[.204 Ruger]], [[.22-250 Remington]], [[.223 Remington]], [[.243 Winchester]], [[.25-06 Remington]], [[.270 Winchester]], [[.270 Winchester Short Magnum]], [[.280 Remington]], [[.300 Winchester Short Magnum]], [[.300 Winchester Magnum]], [[.308 Winchester]], [[.338 Winchester Magnum]], [[.30-06 Springfield]], [[7mm Remington Magnum]], and [[7mm-08 Remington]]<br>\nVariants: Blued, Weather Shield, Predator, Compact<br>\nStock: Polymer<br>\nStatus: In production\n\n== Thompson/Center Arms and the Supreme Court ==\nIn the case of ''[[United States v. Thompson/Center Arms Company|United States v. Thompson/Center Arms Co.]]'' (1992), the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] ruled in the company's favor by deciding that the rifle conversion kit that Thompson sold for their pistols did not constitute a [[short-barreled rifle]] under the [[National Firearms Act]] of 1934.<ref name=\"SCOTUS\">{{ussc|504|505|1992}}</ref>\n\nThe Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms contended that the mere possession of a pistol having a barrel less than sixteen inches (406&nbsp;mm) long, a shoulder stock, and a rifle-length (more than sixteen inches) barrel constituted constructive intent to \"make\" an illegal short-barreled rifle (SBR) (by combining the pistol's frame, the pistol-length barrel, and the shoulder stock) even if the shoulder stock was intended to be used only with the rifle-length barrel.\n\nThe Supreme Court disagreed and its decision clarified the meaning of the term \"make\" in the National Firearms Act by stating that the mere possession of components that theoretically could be assembled in an illegal configuration was not in itself a violation as long as the components could also be assembled into a legal configuration.<ref>{{cite web |title=Case syllabus from Cornell Law School |publisher=Cornell University |year=1992 |url=http://straylight.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/91-0164.ZS.html |accessdate=October 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne argument raised was the example of ammonium-nitrate fertilizer and Diesel oil, which can very often be found together in a farmer's possession (fertilizer for the crops, fuel for the tractor.) Both are lawful, and while they can easily be assembled into the blasting agent known as [[ANFO]], possession of both has never been held to imply (without other evidence) that a farmer was \"making\" explosives.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tcarms.com/ Thompson/Center Arms] corporate website\n*[http://bullberry.com Bullberry Barrel Works], specializing in Contender, G2, and Encore barrels\n*[http://guns.huntingpa.info/index.php/T/C_--_Thompson/Center Muzzleloader Museum Online], listing of some of T/C's muzzleloader guns with pictures and specifications.\n\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Smith & Wesson]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Firearms manufacturer}}\n{{About|Thompson/Center Arms|the unrelated Thompson submachinegun|Thompson submachinegun}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Thompson/Center Arms Inc\n| logo             = TC Logo S&W sm.png\n| logo_size        = 250px\n| type             = [[Subsidiary]]\n| genre            = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = 1965\n| founder          = K. W. Thompson Tool & Warren Center\n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Springfield, Massachusetts]]\n| location_country = [[U.S.]]\n| location         = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Firearms]]\n| products         = [[rifle]]s, [[pistols]]\n| services         = \n| market cap       = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = \n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            =\n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = [[Smith & Wesson]]\n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = http://www.tcarms.com/\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Thompson/Center Arms''' is an American firearms company based in Springfield, Massachusetts. The company is best known for its line of interchangeable-barrel, single-shot pistols and rifles. Thompson/Center also manufactures [[muzzle-loading]] rifles and is credited with creating the resurgence of their use in the 1970s.\n\n==History==\nIn the 1960s, Warren Center developed an unusual break-action, single-shot pistol in his basement workshop that later became known as the Contender. Meanwhile, the K.W. Thompson Tool Company had been searching for a product to manufacture year-round. In 1965, Warren Center joined the K.W. Thompson Tool Company, and together, they announced Warren Center's Contender pistol in 1967. Although it sold for more than comparable hunting revolvers, the flexibility of being able to shoot multiple calibers by simply changing out the barrel and sights and its higher accuracy soon made it popular with handgun hunters.<ref name=\"Zwoll\">{{cite book | last = Van Zwoll | first = Wayne| title = Hunter's Guide to Long-Range Shooting | publisher = Stackpole Books| year = 2006| location = | page = 332 | isbn = }}</ref> As K.W. Thompson Tool began marketing Center's Contender pistol, the company name was changed to Thompson/Center Arms Company. Then, in 1970, Thompson/Center created the modern black powder industry, introducing Warren Center's Hawken-styled black powder muzzle-loader rifle.<ref name=\"CS1\">{{cite book | last = Stephens | first = Charles| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Thompson/Center Contender Pistol: How To Tune, Time, Load, And Shoot For Accuracy | publisher = Paladin Press| year = 1996| location = Boulder, CO | pages = 64 | isbn = 978-0-87364-885-1 }}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2007, Thompson/Center was purchased by [[Smith & Wesson]].<ref>[http://ir.smith-wesson.com/phoenix.zhtml?c=90977&p=irol-newsArticle&ID=942841&highlight 13009 - Smith&Wesson: Press Releases<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nOn December 8, 2010, Smith & Wesson announced that the original Rochester, New Hampshire plant would be closed and manufacturing was transferred to Springfield, Massachusetts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.fosters.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20101210/GJNEWS_01/712109872/0/SEARCH|title=In Rochester: Thompson/Center Arms plant to close|first=Jake| last=O'Donnell|date= December 10, 2010|publisher=Fosters Daily Democrat}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the closure of Thompson/Center arms in Rochester, New Hampshire, Thompson Investment Casting opened in the same town continuing production of metal products for various companies including Smith & Wesson.\n\n==Break-action pistols==\nThompson/Center's success came with the emergence of long range [[handgun hunting]], target shooting, and, especially, [[metallic silhouette shooting]].<ref name=\"Layne\">{{cite journal |url=http://www.shootingtimes.com/ammo/ammunition_st_magseven_200902/ |last=Simpson |first=Layne |title=The Contender's Magnificent 7 |journal=Shooting Times |volume=2009 |issue=2 |date=January 4, 2011 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160921095258/http://www.shootingtimes.com/ammo/ammunition_st_magseven_200902/ |archivedate=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=September 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Their [[break-action]], [[single-shot]] design brought [[rifle]]-like accuracy and power in a handgun, which was a new concept at the time. Originally designed only for interchangeable barrels in [[.38 Special]] and [[.22 LR]], subsequent handgun developments by Thompson/Center led to a wider range of interchangeable barrels for use with many more cartridges. Opening and closing the break-open action is accomplished by squeezing the outside bottom of the trigger guard toward the grip/buttstock, at which time the action opens, and an extractor manually extracts the cartridge.\n\n===Contender===\n{{Main|Thompson/Center Contender}}\n[[File:TC-Contender.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Contender in 45 Colt/.410 with ventilated rib]]\nThe Contender, first introduced in 1967, is a break-action, single-shot pistol or rifle with a number of unique features. The first unique feature is the way the barrel is attached to the frame. By removing the fore-end, a large hinge pin is exposed; by pushing this hinge pin out, the barrel can be removed. Since the sights and extractor remain attached to the barrel in the Contender design, the frame itself contains no cartridge-specific features. A barrel of another caliber can be installed and pinned in place, the fore-end replaced, and the pistol is ready to shoot with a different barrel and pre-aligned sights. This allowed easy changes of calibers, sights, and barrel lengths, with only a flat screwdriver being required for change-out.<ref name=\"Ayoob2012\">{{cite book |last=Ayoob |first=Massad |authorlink=Massad Ayoob |title=Massad Ayoob's Greatest Handguns of the World |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JYmgHFwqT2gC&pg=PA266 |date=May 29, 2012 |publisher=F+W Media |isbn=978-1-4402-2877-3 |pages=241\u2013266 |chapter=Thompson Center Single Shots}}</ref>\n\n===The Encore===\nThe Encore was released in 1983. The Encore uses a different trigger mechanism, designed to be stronger than the original Contender's and to make the break-action easier to open. The Encore uses a considerably larger and stronger frame than the Contender, and accordingly, is found in over 86 cartridges - ranging from [[.22 Hornet]] to the huge [[.416 Rigby]]. There has even been one pistol-length stainless barrel made in .600 Nitro Express. The Encore barrel list also includes shotgun barrels in 28, 20, and 12 gauge, and muzzleloading barrels in .45, .50 caliber, and 12 gauge using #209 shotgun primers. In 2007, Encore rimfire barrels became available in 22 LR and 17 HMR, featuring a unique monoblock design that required no alteration to the frame assembly.\n\nAn upgraded Encore is called the Pro Hunter which generally includes stocks with rubber \"Flex Tech\" inserts and are stainless or carbon steel with weather shielding. There are other slight differences among the rifles including the breech plug on muzzleloader versions.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tcarms.com/firearms/interchangeable-platforms/encore-pro-hunter/platform |publisher=T/C Arms |title=Interchangeable Platforms |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20131213062307/http://www.tcarms.com/firearms/interchangeable-platforms/encore-pro-hunter/platform |archivedate=December 13, 2013 |accessdate=September 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n===The Contender G2===\nThe original Contender, now known as the generation one (G1) Contender, was replaced by the G2 Contender soon after the Encore came out. The G2 Contender is essentially dimensionally the same as the original Contender, but uses an Encore style trigger group. Due to the changes in the trigger mechanism, and to differences in the angle of the grip relative to the boreline of the gun, the buttstocks and pistol grips are different between the G1 and G2 Contenders and will not interchange. The G2, though, uses essentially the same barrels and fore-ends as the original Contender{{Citation needed|date=September 2016}}<!-- Dead link, no archive, no alternate source found beyond the other cited source <ref>http://tcarms.com/TC_IMAGES/TC_Catalog_2006/TC2006_Pg46-47.pdf</ref>--> and barrels will interchange, with the only two exceptions being the G2 muzzleloading barrels, which will only fit the G2 frame, and the Herrett barrels/fore-ends, which are specific for use only on a G1 frame.<ref name=\"Potts\">{{cite journal |last=Potts |first=Bruce |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Thompson Center G2 Contender Rifle Review |journal=Shooting Times |volume=2008 |issue=10 |pages= |publisher= |date=October 1, 2008 |url= | doi= |id= |accessdate= }}</ref>\n\nUnlike the original Contender, dry-firing of the G2 Contender is possible only in the center (safe) hammer position, located on the hammer between the centerfire and rimfire positions. Also, unlike the original Contender, the break-action does not need to be opened/closed (cycled) to practice dry-firing, provided the hammer is lowered between dry firing \"shots\". The adjustability of G2 Contender triggers is also slightly different from the original G1 Contender.\n\n===General legalities===\n\nThe receiver on a Contender, whether G1 or G2, is the portion of the combined grip/buttstock assembly containing the trigger mechanism, and this is legally considered the serial-numbered gun. Hence, barrels with iron or telescopic sights, and even the hinge pin, are all simply gun parts, with no serial numbers, making the choice of changing cartridges from a multitude of rimfire, centerfire rifle and pistol cartridges, and even shotgun shells, very simple.\n\nIt is possible to fit a shoulder stock on a pistol frame in place of a pistol grip, and, when combined with a 16\" or longer barrel (see \"Thompson/Center Arms and the Supreme Court\" below), a Contender may be legally converted from a pistol to a rifle or reversed. Although it is technically possible to fit a pistol grip on an original Contender rifle frame, and use a pistol barrel to convert it from being a rifle to a pistol, this is not legal in the USA, being an illegal creation of a pistol from a rifle. In order to be able to go back and forth, the receiver must have been originally sold as a pistol, per [[Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, Firearms and Explosives|ATF]] rules.\n\n====California Legalities====\n\nSee [[Gun laws in California]]\n*Possession of a Thompson/Center Arms .45/.410 pistol barrel is illegal in California, for both dealers and individuals, and such a barrel may not legally be shipped into the state, or even taken into California for a hunting trip, by reason of it being classified as a short barreled shotgun (SBSG) when used with a Contender receiver.<ref>{{cite web |title=California Dangerous Weapons Control Law ARTICLE 2. UNLAWFUL CARRYING AND POSSESSION OF WEAPONS 12020 |publisher=State of California |year=2008 |url=http://ag.ca.gov/firearms/dwcl/12020.php |accessdate=January 29, 2013 |quote=As used in this section, a \"short-barreled shotgun\" means any of the following: (A) A firearm which is designed or redesigned to fire a fixed shotgun shell and having a barrel or barrels of less than 18 inches in length. (B) A firearm which has an overall length of less than 26 inches and which is designed or redesigned to fire a fixed shotgun shell.}}</ref>\n\n==Muzzleloading rifles==\n[[File:TC-Hawken.JPG|thumb|right|400px|TC Hawken percussion rifle]]\n \nThompson/Center manufactures a variety of [[Muzzleloader|muzzleloading]] rifles of both traditional and inline designs, and sells percussion and flintlock rifles in a wide variety of bore diameters. Some of the better-known models are the Renegade, the [[Hawken rifle|Hawken]], the Big Boar, and the White Mountain.\n\nThe traditional Thompson/Center muzzleloaders are largely responsible for the resurgence of black powder hunting that began in the U.S. in 1970 when Warren Center designed the firm's Hawken-styled rifle. Thompson/Center's reintroduced Hawken-styled rifle with solid brass hardware and an American walnut stock, styled in large part on \"plains rifles\" made by Hawken in the 1800s, has become one of the most-copied firearms designs in history.<ref>{{cite journal | last =Towsley | first = Bryce| authorlink = | coauthors = | title = The Mighty Hawken| journal = Hunting Magazine| volume = 15| issue = 6| pages = | publisher =Petersen | year = 2003| url = | doi = | id = | accessdate = }}</ref> Thompson/Center produced these rifles in the following models and calibers:\n\n'''Cherokee:'''\nBarrel: 24\u201d octagonal, twist: 1:30 (32) & 1:48 (36 & 45),\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 32, 36 & 45,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 1994,\nIgnition: percussion\n\n'''Seneca:'''\nBarrel: 27\u201d octagonal, twist: 1:30 (32) & 1:48 (36 & 45),\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 32, 36 & 45,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 1987,\nIgnition: percussion\n\n'''Hawken:'''\nBarrel: 28\u201d octagonal, twist: 1:48, except 1:66 on 50 cal deep button rifling,\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 45, 50 & 54,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: 45 & 54 discontinued, 50 in production, many special editions,\nIgnition: flint & percussion\n\n'''Cougar:'''\nSpecial edition of the '''Hawken''', satin finish barrel, stainless furniture, highly figured wood\n\n'''Renegade:'''\nBarrel: 26\u201d octagonal, 1:38 (50), 1:48 (50 & 54), 1: 66 (50 deep button rifling), smoothbore (56),\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: 50, 54 & 56, \nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued,\nIgnition: flintlock & percussion\n\n'''Big Boar:'''\nBarrel: 26\u201d octagonal, 1:48,\nTrigger: single,\nCaliber: 58,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued,\nIgnition: percussion\n\n'''Encore 209x50''' \nA modern design muzzleloader that can interchange with centerfire barrels. Based on a single-shot, break-action, the 209x50 is capable of \"[[minute of Angle|minute of angle]]\" accuracy. The 209x50 can handle charges of up to {{convert|150|gr|g}} of black powder or Pyrodex equivalent. Using a 26\" barrel and a {{convert|250|gr|g|adj=on}} bullet with 3 Pyrodex Pellets, it produces a muzzle velocity of 2203&nbsp;ft./second.\n\n'''G2 Contender''' \nA modern design muzzleloader which accepts magnum charges for long range shooting. Charges of up to {{convert|150|gr|g}} of FFG Black Powder or three (3) 50-grain Pyrodex Pellets produce velocities of approximately {{convert|2400|ft/s|m/s|abbr=on}} at the muzzle. The Omega can handle {{convert|150|gr|g}} of Black Powder or Pyrodex equivalent, or three {{convert|50|gr|g|adj=on}} Pyrodex pellets. With its 28\" barrel it burns magnum charges very efficiently.\n\n'''Triumph'''\nThis T/C muzzleloader comes in .50 cal. with a 28\" barrel and composite stock.\n\n==Muzzleloading pistols==\n[[File:Thompson Center Patriot Pistol.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Thompson/Center Patriot Black Powder Muzzleloader Pistol chambered in .45.]]\n[[File:Thompson Center Scout Pistol.jpg|thumb|right|400px|Thompson/Center Scout Black Powder Muzzleloader Pistol chambered in .54.]]\n\n'''Patriot:'''\nBarrel: 9\u201d octagonal,\nTrigger: double set,\nCaliber: .36 & .45,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 1997,\nIgnition: percussion.\n\n'''Scout:'''\nBarrel: 15\u201d round,\nTrigger: single set,\nCaliber: 45, 50 & 54,\nStock: American Walnut,\nStatus: discontinued 199?,\nIgnition: percussion.\n\nA major factory fire at the Thompson/Center factory in 1996 destroyed all tooling and parts for the Scout and Patriot pistols and the Seneca rifle. As a result they were discontinued for sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.telegram.com/article/20121207/column10/112079770 |title=Outdoors: Thompson/Center Arms spirit lives on |date=December 7, 2012 |author=Mark Blazis |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20160921094143/http://www.telegram.com/article/20121207/column10/112079770 |archivedate=September 21, 2016 |accessdate=September 21, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==Bolt action rifles==\n[[File:TC Venture Predator.jpg|thumb|A T/C Venture Predator in Real Tree camouflage]]\n'''Compass'''<br>\nBarrel: 22\", 24\"<br>\nTrigger: Single stage, adjustable<br>\nCaliber: [[.204 Ruger]], [[.22-250 Remington]], [[.223 Remington]], [[.243 Winchester]], [[.270 Winchester]], [[.280 Remington]], [[.300 Winchester Short Magnum]], [[.300 Winchester Magnum]], [[.308 Winchester]], [[6.5mm Creedmoor]], [[.30-06 Springfield]], [[7mm Remington Magnum]], and [[7mm-08 Remington]]<br>\nStock: Polymer<br>\nStatus: In production\n\n'''Venture'''<br>\nBarrel: 22\", 24\"<br>\nTrigger: Single stage, adjustable<br>\nCaliber: [[.204 Ruger]], [[.22-250 Remington]], [[.223 Remington]], [[.243 Winchester]], [[.25-06 Remington]], [[.270 Winchester]], [[.270 Winchester Short Magnum]], [[.280 Remington]], [[.300 Winchester Short Magnum]], [[.300 Winchester Magnum]], [[.308 Winchester]], [[.338 Winchester Magnum]], [[.30-06 Springfield]], [[7mm Remington Magnum]], and [[7mm-08 Remington]]<br>\nVariants: Blued, Weather Shield, Predator, Compact<br>\nStock: Polymer<br>\nStatus: In production\n\n== Thompson/Center Arms and the Supreme Court ==\nIn the case of ''[[United States v. Thompson/Center Arms Company|United States v. Thompson/Center Arms Co.]]'' (1992), the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] ruled in the company's favor by deciding that the rifle conversion kit that Thompson sold for their pistols did not constitute a [[short-barreled rifle]] under the [[National Firearms Act]] of 1934.<ref name=\"SCOTUS\">{{ussc|504|505|1992}}</ref>\n\nThe Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco, and Firearms contended that the mere possession of a pistol having a barrel less than sixteen inches (406&nbsp;mm) long, a shoulder stock, and a rifle-length (more than sixteen inches) barrel constituted constructive intent to \"make\" an illegal short-barreled rifle (SBR) (by combining the pistol's frame, the pistol-length barrel, and the shoulder stock) even if the shoulder stock was intended to be used only with the rifle-length barrel.\n\nThe Supreme Court disagreed and its decision clarified the meaning of the term \"make\" in the National Firearms Act by stating that the mere possession of components that theoretically could be assembled in an illegal configuration was not in itself a violation as long as the components could also be assembled into a legal configuration.<ref>{{cite web |title=Case syllabus from Cornell Law School |publisher=Cornell University |year=1992 |url=http://straylight.law.cornell.edu/supct/html/91-0164.ZS.html |accessdate=October 21, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOne argument raised was the example of ammonium-nitrate fertilizer and Diesel oil, which can very often be found together in a farmer's possession (fertilizer for the crops, fuel for the tractor.) Both are lawful, and while they can easily be assembled into the blasting agent known as [[ANFO]], possession of both has never been held to imply (without other evidence) that a farmer was \"making\" explosives.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tcarms.com/ Thompson/Center Arms] corporate website\n*[http://bullberry.com Bullberry Barrel Works], specializing in Contender, G2, and Encore barrels\n*[http://guns.huntingpa.info/index.php/T/C_--_Thompson/Center Muzzleloader Museum Online], listing of some of T/C's muzzleloader guns with pictures and specifications.\n\n[[Category:Firearm manufacturers of the United States]]\n[[Category:Smith & Wesson]]\n", "name_user": "Gjs238", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thompson/Center_Arms"}
{"title_page": "Vince Gibson", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Vince Gibson\n| image = Coach Vince Gibson.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Gibson pictured in ''Jambalaya 1983'', Tulane yearbook\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|1933|3|27}}\n| birth_place = [[Birmingham, Alabama]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|2012|1|10|1933|3|27}}\n| death_place = [[Kenner, Louisiana]]\n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1954\u20131955\n| player_team1 = [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]]\n| player_positions = [[Guard (American and Canadian football)|Guard]]\n| coach_years1 = 1956\u20131958\n| coach_team1 = [[South Georgia State College|South Georgia JC]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1959\u20131963\n| coach_team2 = [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]] (assistant)\n| coach_years3 = 1964\u20131966\n| coach_team3 = [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]])\n| coach_years4 = 1967\u20131974\n| coach_team4 = [[Kansas State Wildcats football|Kansas State]]\n| coach_years5 = 1975\u20131979\n| coach_team5 = [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| coach_years6 = 1980\u20131982\n| coach_team6 = [[Tulane Green Wave football|Tulane]]\n| coach_years7 = 1992\n| coach_team7 = [[New Orleans Night]]\n| overall_record = 75\u201398\u20132 (college)<br />0\u201310 (AFL)\n| bowl_record = 0\u20132\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = [[Big Eight Conference]] COY (1970)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Vince Gibson''' (March 27, 1933 \u2013 January 10, 2012) was an [[American football]] player and coach.  He served as head football coach at [[Kansas State University]] (1967\u20131974), the [[University of Louisville]] (1975\u20131979), and [[Tulane University]] (1980\u20131982), compiling a career [[college football]] record of 75\u201398\u20132.  In 1992, he coached the [[New Orleans Night]] of the [[Arena Football League]], tallying a mark of 0\u201310.<ref>{{cite web | title = List of AFL Coaches | url = http://www.arenafan.com/history/?page=coaches | accessdate = March 31, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and playing career==\nGibson was born and raised in [[Birmingham, Alabama]].  He graduated from [[Florida State University]] in 1955, where he received two letters playing as an offensive guard for the Seminoles.<ref name=reference2>{{cite web | title = Alabama Sports Hall of Fame profile | url = http://www.ashof.org/index.php?src=directory&view=company&srctype=display&back=company&id=324&sor=name&search=Gibson&submenu=Inductees&pos=0,15,1 | accessdate = March 31, 2011}}</ref>  He entered the coaching profession immediately after graduation.\n\n==Coaching career==\nGibson's first football coaching position was at [[South Georgia State College|South Georgia College]] in 1956, a position he held for three years.  At South Georgia, Gibson served as the sole assistant under head coach [[Bobby Bowden]], who had grown up in the same Birmingham neighborhood as Gibson.<ref name=Bowden>{{Cite news | title = Vince Gibson, Former College Football Coach | newspaper = The Palm Beach Post | date = December 24, 2009 | url = http://www.palmbeachpost.com/sports/vince-gibson-former-college-football-coach-146592.html | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Bobby and His Boys | newspaper = The Ledger | date = December 1, 2009 | url = http://www.theledger.com/article/20091201/SPORTS0701/912019939?p=2&tc=pg | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>  Following his stint at South Georgia, Gibson returned to his [[alma mater]] Florida State to work as an assistant coach from 1959 to 1963.  Before leaving Florida State, Gibson also helped to get Bowden hired as an assistant at that school, where Bowden eventually became head coach.<ref name=Bowden/><ref>{{Cite news | title = College Football Has Void Without Bobby Bowden | newspaper = NewOrleans.com | date = August 25, 2010 | url = http://www.neworleans.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=460597&Itemid=578 | archive-url = https://archive.is/20120904195339/http://www.neworleans.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=460597&Itemid=578 | url-status = dead | archive-date = September 4, 2012 }}</ref>  Gibson next served as [[defensive coordinator]] at the [[University of Tennessee]] from 1964 to 1966.\n\n===Kansas State===\nPrior to the 1967 football season, Gibson was hired as head coach at [[Kansas State University]].  When he was hired, the school was mired in a 21-game winless streak and had not enjoyed a winning season since 1954, but he promised the Wildcat fans, \"We gonna win!\"<ref name=reference1>{{Cite news | title = Sanctions Still Trouble Cats' Gibson | newspaper = The Topeka Capital-Journal | date = October 14, 2000 | url = http://cjonline.com/stories/101400/spo_ksuhof.shtml | access-date = November 10, 2008 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080915111216/http://cjonline.com/stories/101400/spo_ksuhof.shtml | archive-date = September 15, 2008 | url-status = dead | df = mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nGibson's first season at Kansas State ended with a 1\u20139 record, but the next year the team showed significant improvement.  Behind sophomore quarterback [[Lynn Dickey]], the 1968 squad earned the school's first national ranking in the [[AP Poll]] and shut out [[1968 Nebraska Cornhuskers football team|Nebraska]] in Lincoln for the school's first victory over NU in a decade.  That same season, Kansas State also moved into a [[Bill Snyder Family Football Stadium|new football stadium]].\n\nGibson truly began to deliver on his promise to win during the 1969 season.  The team started 2\u20130 before second-ranked [[1969 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|Penn State]] arrived to play in [[Manhattan, Kansas]].  Penn State ultimately finished the 1969 season undefeated, but Kansas State provided them with one of their toughest tests in a 17\u201314 game.  Following the loss to Penn State, Kansas State reeled off three straight victories, including a win over defending conference champion [[Kansas Jayhawks football|Kansas]] in the first [[Governor's Cup (Kansas)|Governor's Cup]] game, and a 59\u201321 blowout of #11 [[1969 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]], which was Kansas State's first win over the Sooners since 1934 and the largest loss in Oklahoma's history.  K-State would not beat another ranked team until 1993, when [[Bill Snyder]] lead the team to victory over Oklahoma again.  After the 1969 Oklahoma game, Kansas State sported a 5\u20131 record and a #12 national ranking in the AP Poll.  This was the high-point of the season, as the team lost its last four games to finish 5\u20135.  Nevertheless, in only his third season, Gibson had dramatically improved the program.\n\nPrior to the 1970 season, Gibson was named the pre-season national coach of the year by ''[[Playboy Magazine]]''.  The season that followed was up-and-down but ultimately disappointing despite a winning record and a second-place finish in the [[Big Eight Conference]].  Kansas State won at Oklahoma and defeated eighth-ranked [[Colorado Buffaloes football|Colorado]], but the season was soured by non-conference defeats and a blow-out loss to Nebraska in the final conference game of the year with the conference title on the line.  The worst news of the season came on October 7, 1970, when the conference slapped the Wildcats with three years' probation for recruiting violations.  Most seriously, the Wildcats were banned from bowl games and live television for one year.  Gibson later said that the sanctions\u2014the result of what he called an immature quarrel with Kansas coach [[Pepper Rodgers]]\u2014destroyed his program.<ref name=reference1/>\n\nKansas State stagnated following the 1970 season, with Gibson's teams hovering below the .500 mark for the next four years.  Quarterback [[Steve Grogan]] provided some excitement during the 1973 and 1974 seasons, but it was never enough to provide a winning record.  Gibson decided to leave Kansas State following the 1974 season with a final record of 33\u201352.\n\n===Louisville and Tulane===\nFollowing his term at Kansas State, Gibson served as head football coach at the [[University of Louisville]] from 1975 to 1979.  His record at Louisville was 25\u201329\u20132, and in 1977 he took the school to the third [[bowl game]] in its history, the second [[Independence Bowl]].  While at Louisville, Gibson coined the nickname \"Red Rage\" for the football team, a related carry over from the \"Purple Pride\" at K-State.  While no longer used as a moniker for the football team, the term Red Rage has been used over the years for various organizations.  Currently, the U of L Marching Band is introduced as the [[The University of Louisville \"RED RAGE!\" Marching Band|\"RED RAGE!\" Marching Band]].  NFL notables from Louisville during Gibson's tenure include [[Otis Wilson]] of the [[Chicago Bears]] and [[Dwayne Woodruff]] of the [[Pittsburgh Steelers]] and Joe Jacoby of the [[Washington Redskins]] and Mark Clayton of the [[Miami Dolphins]].\n\nFrom 1980 to 1982 Gibson coached at [[Tulane University]], posting an overall record of 17\u201317.  Gibson defeated [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] in two out of his three seasons at Tulane and also coached the Green Wave to an appearance in the [[1980 Hall of Fame Classic]].  While at Tulane, Gibson was known as \"Vegas Vince\" for his risk taking play calling.\n\n===Awards===\nGibson was named the [[Big Eight Conference]] Coach of the Year in 1970.  He was also selected to coach the North squad in the 1971 [[North\u2013South Shrine Game]].  Gibson is enshrined in the [[Alabama Sports Hall of Fame]] and the Kansas State University Athletics Hall of Fame.\n\n==Death==\nGibson died in 2012 in [[Kenner, Louisiana]] after a battle with [[amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]]. He was 78.\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===College===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = no }}\n{{CF