ubar-come-from.1643805/ |website=ananadtech.com |publisher=Anandtech |accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nThis particular FUBAR acronym survived WWII and for a time in the 70s, found its way into the lexicon of management consultants. Their use of the term,(though the word, \u201crear,\u201d is not normally used to describe the vantage point of senior corporate executives) may have come about as the result of their frequent conclusions that the cause of corporate problems (inefficiencies and ineffectiveness causing poor profitability or a negative bottom line) rested not with rank and file workers, but with executives, particularly senior executives - the equivalent of senior military officers. Therefore, FUBAR (Fucked Up By Assholes in the Rear) still applied well, even if in reality it should have been rendered as FUBAT (Fucked Up By Assholes at the Top).\n\n===FUBU===\n{{distinguish|FUBU}}\n''FUBU'' (''Fucked/fouled Up Beyond all Understanding'') was also used during World War II.\n\n===SNAFU===\n{{main|SNAFU}}\n''SNAFU'' is widely used to stand for the sarcastic expression ''Situation Normal: All Fucked Up'', as a well-known example of military acronym slang. However, the military acronym originally stood for \"Status Nominal: All Fucked Up.\" It is sometimes [[Expurgation|bowdlerized]] to ''all fouled up'' or similar.<ref>{{cite web|last=Neary|first=Lynn|title=Fifty Years of 'The Cat in the Hat'| publisher=[[NPR|National Public Radio]]|quote= 'Situation Normal&nbsp; ... All Fouled Up,' as the first SNAFU animated cartoon put it|url= https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=7651308|access-date=2008-01-08}}</ref> It means that the situation is bad, but that this is a normal state of affairs. It is typically used in a joking manner to describe something that is working as intended. The acronym is believed to have originated in the [[United States Marine Corps]] during [[World War II]].{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' magazine used the term in their June 16, 1942 issue: \"Last week U.S. citizens knew that gasoline rationing and rubber requisitioning were snafu.\"<ref name=\"OED\" /> Most reference works, including the [[Random House Webster's Unabridged Dictionary]], supply an origin date of 1940\u20131944, generally attributing it to the [[United States Army]].\n\n[[Rick Atkinson]] ascribes the origin of SNAFU, [[#FUBAR|FUBAR]], and a bevy of other terms to cynical [[G.I. (military)|G.I.s]] ridiculing the Army's penchant for acronyms.<ref>{{Cite book |title=The Day of Battle: The War in Sicily and Italy, 1943\u20131944 |series=The Liberation Trilogy |first=Rick |last=Atkinson |year=2007 |publisher=Henry Holt |isbn=978-0-8050-6289-2 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/dayofbattlewarin00atki }}</ref>\n\n[[Private Snafu]] is the title character of a series of military instructional films, most of which were written by [[Dr. Seuss|Theodor \"Dr. Seuss\" Geisel]], [[P. D. Eastman|Philip D. Eastman]], and [[Munro Leaf]].<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1111/j.1540-5931.2007.00404.x|title=Children's Literature Goes to War: Dr. Seuss, P. D. Eastman, Munro Leaf, and the Private SNAFU Films (1943?46)|journal=The Journal of Popular Culture|volume=40|issue=3|pages=468|year=2007|last1=Nel|first1=Philip}}</ref>\n\nIn modern usage, ''snafu'' is sometimes used as an [[interjection]], though it is mostly now used as a noun. ''Snafu'' also sometimes refers to a bad situation, mistake, or cause of the trouble. It is more commonly used in modern [[vernacular]] to describe running into an error or problem that is large and unexpected. For example, in 2005, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an article titled \"Hospital Staff Cutback Blamed for Test Result Snafu\".<ref>{{cite news |title=Hospital Staff Cutback Blamed for Test Result Snafu |last=Santora |first=Marc |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/05/19/nyregion/19pap.html?scp=4&sq=snafu&st=cse |newspaper=The New York Times |date=May 19, 2005 |access-date=29 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe attribution of ''SNAFU'' to the American military is not universally accepted: it has also been attributed to the [[United Kingdom|British]],<ref>{{Cite book |title=Rawson's Dictionary of Euphemisms and Other Doubletalk: Being a Compilation of Linguistic Fig Leaves and Verbal Flourishes for Artful Users of the English Language |year=1995 |location=New York |publisher=Crown |first=Hugh |last=Rawson |isbn=978-0-517-70201-7}}</ref> although the Oxford English Dictionary gives its origin and first recorded use as the U.S. military.<ref name=\"OED\" />\n\nIn a wider study of military slang, Frederick Elkin noted in 1946 that there \"are a few acceptable substitutes, such as 'screw up' or 'mess up,' but these do not have the emphasis value of the obscene equivalent.\" He considered the expression ''SNAFU'' to be \"a caricature of Army direction. The soldier resignedly accepts his own less responsible position and expresses his cynicism at the inefficiency of Army authority.\" He also noted that \"the expression \u2026 is coming into general civilian use.\"<ref>{{Citation| last= Elkin| first= Frederick| date=March  1946|title= The Soldier's Language| journal= American Journal of Sociology| volume= 51| issue= 5 Human Behavior in Military Society| publisher= The University of Chicago Press| pages= 414\u2013422| jstor= 2771105}}</ref>\n\n===An Imperial FU===\n''An Imperial FU'' (''An Imperial Fuck Up'') was used during [[World War I]] by soldiers of the outlying [[British Empire]], e.g. Canada, Australia, New Zealand, the [[Union of South Africa]], Kenya, [[Tanganyika]], [[India]], in reference to odd/conflicting orders from [[United Kingdom|British authorities]]. Note that during World War I, the British Empire had an ''[[Imperial War Cabinet]]'', and the troops from Australia were called the [[First Australian Imperial Force|Australian Imperial Force]] (AIF), not to be confused with the [[American Expeditionary Forces|AEF]], the [[American Expeditionary Forces]] of WW I, or the [[Allied Expeditionary Force]] of WW II.\n\n===SUSFU===\n''SUSFU'' (S''ituation Unchanged: Still Fucked Up'') is closely related to ''SNAFU''.\n\n''SNAFU'' and ''SUSFU'' were first recorded in ''[[American Notes and Queries]]'' in their September 13, 1941 issue.<ref name=\"OED\">{{Cite book |title=A Supplement to the Oxford English Dictionary |editor=Burchfield, R.W. |volume=Volume IV Se-Z |year=1986 |location=Oxford |publisher=Clarendon |isbn=978-0-19-861115-8}}</ref>\n\n===TARFU===\n''TARFU'' (''Totally And Royally Fucked Up'' or ''Things Are Really Fucked Up'') was also used during World War II.\n\nThe [[1944 in film|1944]] U.S. Army animated shorts ''[[Three Brothers (1944 film)|Three Brothers]]'' and ''Private Snafu Presents Seaman Tarfu In The Navy'' (both directed by [[Friz Freleng]]), feature the characters Private Snafu, Private Fubar, and Seaman Tarfu (with a [[cameo appearance|cameo]] by [[Bugs Bunny]]).<ref name=\"three\">{{cite web|publisher = [[Internet Archive]]|title = Private Snafu \u2013 Three Brothers (1944)|url = https://archive.org/details/PrivateSnafu-ThreeBrothers1944|accessdate = 2011-03-22}}</ref><ref name=\"snafu\">{{cite web|author =Pietro Shakarian|title =Situation Normal All Fucked Up:A History of Private Snafu|work =goldenagecartoons.com|url =http://looney.goldenagecartoons.com/miscelooneyous/snafu/|accessdate =2008-05-05|url-status =dead|archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20080512092007/http://looney.goldenagecartoons.com/miscelooneyous/snafu/|archivedate =2008-05-12}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of government and military acronyms]]\n* [[List of U.S. government and military acronyms]]\n** [[List of United States Marine Corps acronyms and expressions]]\n** [[List of U.S. Navy acronyms and expressions]]\n** [[List of U.S. Air Force acronyms and expressions]]\n* [[FUBAR (film)|''FUBAR'' (film)]], a 2002 [[mockumentary]] by [[Michael Dowse]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite book |last=Colby |first=Elbridge |date=1943 |title=Army Talk: A Familiar Dictionary of Soldier Speech |url= |location= |publisher=Princeton University Press |page= |isbn= |author-link= |ASIN=B00725XTA4}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dickson |first=Paul |date=2014 |title=War Slang: American Fighting Words & Phrases Since the Civil War |url= |location= |publisher=Courier Corporation |page= |isbn=9780486797168 |author-link=Paul Dickson (writer)}}\n* {{cite book|last=Hakim|first=Joy|title=A History of Us: War, Peace and all that Jazz|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]]|year=1995| location=New York|isbn=0-19-509514-6}}\n* {{cite news|last=Jacobson|first=Gary|date=August 14, 1994|work=[[The Dallas Morning News]]|title=Humor best way to remove last of 'Bohicans' resistance|page=7H|accessdate=7 November 2008|url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DM&p_theme=dm&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0ED3D4DDA7D891CC&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D}}\n* {{cite news|last=Stromberg|first=Rich|date=May 10, 2005|work=[[UWIRE]]|title=Grab your ankles and say BOHICA|accessdate=7 November 2008|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-108572048.html}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}\n\nBOHICA by Scott Barnes published 1987<ref>BOHICA Book, published 1987</ref>\n\n==External links==\n{{Wiktionary|SNAFU|FUBAR|BOHICA}}\n* [[:Wiktionary:Appendix:Glossary of military slang]]\n* [[:Wiktionary:Category:Military slang by language]]\n* [http://dictionary.com/browse/SNAFU Meaning of SNAFU on Dictionary.com]\n* [http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=SNAFU&Find=Find Acronym Finder's SNAFU entry]\n* [http://www.acronymfinder.com/af-query.asp?String=exact&Acronym=FUBAR&Find=Find Acronym Finder's FUBAR entry]\n* [https://archive.org/details/CommandPerformance Command Performance] Episode 101 from 15 Jan 1944 ([https://archive.org/download/CommandPerformance/CP_44-01-15_ep101-Frances_Langford__Virginia_OBrien.mp3 MP3 6M]) includes a song about SNAFU by the [[Spike Jones]] band.\n* [http://www2.iath.virginia.edu/sixties/HTML_docs/Resources/Glossary/Sixties_Term_Gloss_K_P.html Glossary of Military Terms & Slang from the Vietnam War]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090323040108/http://www.snafu.com/Snafu/SnafuStory.html How the term SNAFU originated]\n* [https://archive.org/details/home_front Internet Archive: Private SNAFU \u2013 The Home Front (1943)] \u2013 This is one of 26 Private SNAFU cartoons made by the US Army Signal Corps to educate and boost the morale of the troops.\n* [http://catb.org/~esr/jargon/html/S/SNAFU-principle.html SNAFU Principle]\n* [http://www.the-snafu-special.com/ The SNAFU Special \u2013 Official website of the C-47 #43-15073]\n* [[World Wide Words]], [[Michael Quinion]], [http://www.worldwidewords.org/articles/asye.htm ''Acronyms for your Enjoyment''.]\n\n[[Category:Military slang and jargon]]\n[[Category:Profanity]]\n[[Category:Lists of government and military acronyms|Military slang]]\n", "name_user": "AlphaMikeOmega", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 941773497 by214.18.213.148(talk) Typo)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_military_slang_terms"}
{"title_page": "Willa Brown", "text_new": "{{short description|Aviator, educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[U.S. Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = January 22, 1906\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil Rights]] Leader, first African American Officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], first African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = Wilbur Hardaway<br>[[Cornelius Coffey]]<br>Rev. J. H. Chappell\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter=Brown, Willa|title=[[American National Biography]]|chapter-url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html|publisher=Oxford University Press}} ''Subscription needed.''</ref> She was the first [[African Americans|African-American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African-American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], the first African-American officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], and the first woman in the United States to have both a pilot's license and a mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /> A lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in flight and in the military, Brown not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps|U.S. Army Air Corp]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Cornelius Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], the first private flight training academy in the United States owned and operated by African-Americans. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom went on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |author= Kelli Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016|first = |last = }}</ref>\n\nWell after the Coffey School closed in 1945, Brown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]]. She organized flight schools for children, she ran for Congress three times (1946, 1948, and 1950), she was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and she taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at the age of 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Brown Chappell was born in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].\n\nIn 1927, she graduated from [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] with a degree in business. She received an M.B.A. from [[Northwestern University]] in 1937.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=0-253-32774-1|pages=184\u2013185|chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref>\n\nAs a young high school teacher in [[Gary, Indiana]], and later as a social worker in Chicago, Brown felt that her talents were not being put to their greatest use. Consequently, she sought greater challenges and adventures in life and pushed actively against the limited boundaries of career fields normally open to African Americans.\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nShe decided to learn to fly, studying with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic at one of Chicago's racially segregated airports. In 1938, she became the first African American woman who earned a private pilot's license in the United States.<ref>{{cite Journal|magazine=AOPA Pilot|date=May 2014|page=41}}</ref> (Fellow Chicagoan and aviator [[Bessie Coleman]] had to go to France for her license in 1921).<ref>{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 |author=Editorial Board | location=Sec. 1 |page=14}}</ref> Later, Brown and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nTogether with Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters, Willa Brown helped form the National Airmen's Association of America in 1939, whose main goal was to get black aviation cadets into the United States military. As the organization's national secretary and the president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. \n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe continually lobbied the government for integration of black pilots into the segregated Army Air Corps and the federal Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), the system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. Subsequently, when Congress finally voted to allow separate-but-equal participation of blacks in civilian flight training programs, the Coffey School of Aeronautics was chosen for participation in the CPTP.\n\nBrown became the coordinator for the CPTP in Chicago. Later, her flight school was also selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program at the Tuskegee Institute.<ref name=\"cap-bio\"/>\n\nWilla Brown eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority and later was a member of the Federal Aviation Administration's Women's Advisory Board. She was the first black female officer in the Civil Air Patrol and the first black woman to hold a commercial pilot's license in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Gubert\n| first1 = Betty Kaplan\n| title = Willa Brown\n| url = http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html?a=1&g=f&co=black%20history%20month%20OR%20womens%20history%20month&uc=1&uc=2&n=Willa%20Brown&ia=-at&ib=-bib&d=10&ss=0&q=1\n| website = American National Biography Online\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Gubert|first1=Betty Kaplan|last2=Sawyer|first2=Miriam|last3=Fannin|first3=Caroline M.|title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science|date=2002|publisher=Oryx Press|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=9781573562461|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Aviator, educator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name        = Willa Brown\n|image       = \"Willa Beatrice Brown, a 31-year-old Negro American, serves her country by training pilots for the U.S. Army Air Forces. - NARA - 535717.jpg\n|alt         =\n|caption     = Brown as a lieutenant in the [[U.S. Civil Air Patrol]]\n|birth_date  = January 22, 1906\n|birth_place = [[Glasgow, Kentucky]]\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|mf=yes|1992|07|18|1906|01|22}}\n|death_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]]\n|nationality = [[United States|American]]\n|other_names =\n|known_for   = [[Civil Rights]] Leader, first African American Officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], first African American woman to run for [[United States Congress]]\n|occupation  = [[Pilot (aeronautics)|Pilot]], [[Lobbyist]], [[Activist]], [[Teacher]]\n|spouse   = Wilbur Hardaway<br>[[Cornelius Coffey]]<br>Rev. J. H. Chappell\n}}\n'''Willa Beatrice Brown''' (January 22, 1906 \u2013 July 18, 1992) was an American [[Pilot (aeronautics)|aviator]], [[lobbyist]], [[teacher]], and [[Civil Rights Movement|civil rights]] activist.<ref>{{Cite book|chapter=Brown, Willa|title=[[American National Biography]]|chapter-url=http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html|publisher=Oxford University Press}} ''Subscription needed.''</ref> She was the first [[African Americans|African-American]] woman to earn a pilot's license in the United States,<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|title = Brown, Willa B. (1906\u20131992) |url = http://www.blackpast.org/aah/brown-willa-b-1906-1992|website = The Black Past|author=Davis, Edmond|access-date = 2016-02-09}}</ref> the first African-American woman to run for the [[United States Congress]], the first African-American officer in the US [[Civil Air Patrol]], and the first woman in the United States to have both a pilot's license and a mechanic's license.<ref name=\":0\" /> A lifelong advocate for gender and racial equality in flight and in the military, Brown not only lobbied the U.S. government to integrate the [[United States Army Air Corps|U.S. Army Air Corp]] and include African Americans in the Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), but also co-founded the [[Cornelius Coffey School of Aeronautics]] with [[Cornelius Coffey]], which was the first private flight training academy in the United States owned and operated by African Americans. She trained hundreds of pilots, several of whom would go on to become [[Tuskegee Airmen]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Our History {{!}} 99s in Aviation History {{!}} Women in Aviation |author= Kelli Grant|url = http://www.ninety-nines.org/women-in-aviation-article.htm|website = The Ninety-Nines, Inc.|access-date =February 9, 2016|first = |last = }}</ref>\n\nWell after the Coffey School closed in 1945, Brown remained politically and socially active in [[Chicago]]. She organized flight schools for children, she ran for Congress three times (1946, 1948, and 1950), she was an active member of the Westside Community Church, and she taught in the Chicago Public School System until 1971, when she retired at the age of 65.\n\n== Early life ==\nWilla Brown Chappell was born in [[Glasgow, Kentucky]].\n\nIn 1927, she graduated from [[Indiana State University|Indiana State Teachers College]] with a degree in business. She received an M.B.A. from [[Northwestern University]] in 1937.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite book|title=Black Women in America: An Historical Encyclopedia|year=1994|publisher=Indiana University Press|location=Bloomington|isbn=0-253-32774-1|pages=184\u2013185|chapter=Brown, Willa Beatrice (1906\u20131992)|first=Elizabeth Hadley|last=Freydberg}}</ref>\n\nAs a young high school teacher in [[Gary, Indiana]], and later as a social worker in Chicago, Brown felt that her talents were not being put to their greatest use. Consequently, she sought greater challenges and adventures in life and pushed actively against the limited boundaries of career fields normally open to African Americans.\n\n== Aviation career ==\n[[File:Young Willa Brown.jpg|thumb|left|Willa Brown as a young woman, standing on an airfield]]\nShe decided to learn to fly, studying with [[Cornelius Coffey]], a certified flight instructor and expert aviation mechanic at one of Chicago's racially segregated airports. In 1938, she became the first African American woman who earned a private pilot's license in the United States.<ref>{{cite Journal|magazine=AOPA Pilot|date=May 2014|page=41}}</ref> (Fellow Chicagoan and aviator [[Bessie Coleman]] had to go to France for her license in 1921).<ref>{{cite news |title=Chicago and the Tuskegee Airmen |work=Chicago Tribune |date=January 19, 2015 |author=Editorial Board | location=Sec. 1 |page=14}}</ref> Later, Brown and Coffey married and established the Coffey School of Aeronautics at Harlem Airport in Chicago, where they trained black pilots and aviation mechanics.<ref name=\"cap-bio\">{{cite web |last1=Montague |first1=Carlos |title=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |url=https://www.cap.news/willa-brown-pioneer-for-female--african-american-aviation/ |website=Willa Brown: Pioneer for Female & African American Aviation |accessdate=30 March 2020 |language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nTogether with Cornelius Coffey and Enoch P. Waters, Willa Brown helped form the National Airmen's Association of America in 1939, whose main goal was to get black aviation cadets into the United States military. As the organization's national secretary and the president of the Chicago branch, Brown became an activist for racial equality. \n[[File:LIEUT. WILLA BROWN - AVIATRIX-MAKER OF PILOTS - NARA - 535627.tif|thumb|Office for Emergency Management publication featuring Brown]]\nShe continually lobbied the government for integration of black pilots into the segregated Army Air Corps and the federal Civilian Pilot Training Program (CPTP), the system established by the Civil Aeronautics Authority to provide a pool of civilian pilots for use during national emergencies. Subsequently, when Congress finally voted to allow separate-but-equal participation of blacks in civilian flight training programs, the Coffey School of Aeronautics was chosen for participation in the CPTP.\n\nBrown became the coordinator for the CPTP in Chicago. Later, her flight school was also selected by the U.S. Army to provide black trainees for the Air Corps pilot training program at the Tuskegee Institute.<ref name=\"cap-bio\"/>\n\nWilla Brown eventually became the coordinator of war-training service for the Civil Aeronautics Authority and later was a member of the Federal Aviation Administration's Women's Advisory Board. She was the first black female officer in the Civil Air Patrol and the first black woman to hold a commercial pilot's license in the United States.<ref>{{cite web |title=WILLA BROWN |url=http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |website=Hill Air Force Base |accessdate=30 March 2020 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160328143509/http://www.hill.af.mil/library/factsheets/factsheet.asp?id=5858 |archivedate=28 Mar 2016 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Brown was awarded the Distinguished Alumni Award by the [[Indiana University of Pennsylvania|Indiana State University]] Alumni Association.\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Gubert\n| first1 = Betty Kaplan\n| title = Willa Brown\n| url = http://www.anb.org/articles/20/20-01864.html?a=1&g=f&co=black%20history%20month%20OR%20womens%20history%20month&uc=1&uc=2&n=Willa%20Brown&ia=-at&ib=-bib&d=10&ss=0&q=1\n| website = American National Biography Online\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite web\n| last1 = Freydberg\n| first1 = Elizabeth Amelia Hadley\n| title = Aviation\n| url = http://search.credoreference.com/content/entry/rcuswh/aviation/0\n| website = Credo\n| publisher = Houghton Mifflin Company\n| accessdate = 9 September 2017\n}}\n\n*{{cite book|last1=Gubert|first1=Betty Kaplan|last2=Sawyer|first2=Miriam|last3=Fannin|first3=Caroline M.|title=Distinguished African Americans in aviation and space science|date=2002|publisher=Oryx Press|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=9781573562461|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/distinguishedafr00gube}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Johnson|first1=Jesse J.|title=Black women in the Armed Forces, 1942-1974 : (a pictorial history)|date=1974|publisher=Johnson|location=Hampton, Va.|isbn=9780915044115|edition=1st}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Gibson|first1=Karen Bush|title=Women aviators : 26 stories of pioneer flights, daring missions, and record-setting journeys|date=2013|publisher=Chicago Review Press|location=Chicago, Ill.|isbn=9781613745403|edition=1st|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/womenaviators26s0000gibs}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Kentucky Women Remembered|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brown, Willa}}\n[[Category:1906 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:African-American educators]]\n[[Category:20th-century American educators]]\n[[Category:African-American female military personnel]]\n[[Category:American women in World War II]]\n[[Category:Indiana State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Women in the United States Army]]\n[[Category:American female aviators]]\n[[Category:Kentucky women aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American aviators]]\n[[Category:African-American female aviators]]\n", "name_user": "Atsme", "label": "safe", "comment": "CE", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willa_Brown"}
{"title_page": "Mace Windu", "text_new": "{{Redirect|Windu|the cycle of 8 lunar years|Javanese calendar}}\n{{short description|Fictional character in Star Wars}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mace Windu\n| image              = Mace Windu.png\n| caption            = Samuel L. Jackson as Mace Windu\n| series             = [[Star Wars]]\n| first              = ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace|The Phantom Menace]]'' (1999)\n| last               = ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker|The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (2019)\n| creator            = [[George Lucas]]\n| occupation         = [[Jedi]]\n| title              = {{plainlist|\n* Jedi (former)\n* Jedi Knight (former)\n* Jedi Master\n* Republic General (during the Clone Wars)\n}}\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| lbl21              = Homeworld\n| data21             = [[List of Star Wars planets and moons#Haruun Kal|Haruun Kal]]\n| affiliation        = [[Jedi|Jedi Order]]<br>[[Galactic Republic]]\n| portrayer          = [[Samuel L. Jackson]]\n| voice              = {{unbulleted list|[[Terrence C. Carson]] <br> ([[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2002 video game)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' (video game)]], ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'', [[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith (video game)|''Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith'' (video game)]], ''[[Star Wars: Battlefront II (2005 video game)|Star Wars: Battlefront II]]'', ''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' (TV series), ''[[Star Wars Battlefront: Elite Squadron]]'', ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars: Republic Heroes]]'', ''[[Kinect Star Wars]]'' and ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]'')|Samuel L. Jackson <br>([[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' (film)]], ''[[Lego Star Wars III: The Clone Wars]]'' and ''Episode IX'')|[[Kevin Michael Richardson]]<br> (''[[Star Wars Episode I: Jedi Power Battles|Jedi Power Battles]]'', ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: Jedi Starfighter|Jedi Starfighter]]'')|[[Donald Glover]] <br>(''[[Robot Chicken: Star Wars Episode III|Robot Chicken]]'')|[[Adrian Holmes]] <br>(''[[Lego Star Wars: The Yoda Chronicles|The Yoda Chronicles]]'' and ''[[Lego Star Wars: Droid Tales|Droid Tales]]'')}}\n}}\n\n'''Mace Windu'''  is a [[fictional character]] in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise, portrayed by [[actor]] [[Samuel L. Jackson]] in the [[Star Wars prequel trilogy|prequel films]] and voiced by Jackson in the animated film ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' while voice actor [[Terrence C. Carson]] voices him in other projects, such as [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|''The Clone Wars'' television series]]. He is a human male, a [[Jedi master]] on the [[Jedi Council|High Council]] and one of the last members of the order's upper echelons before the [[Galactic Republic]]'s fall. Despite the [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|Clone Wars]] causing him to question his most firmly held beliefs,<ref name=\"Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|first1=Stephen J.|last1=Sansweet|first2=Pablo|last2=Hidalgo|first3=Bob|last3=Vitas|title=The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia|publisher=[[LucasBooks]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2008|ISBN= 978-0345477637}}</ref> he is a staunch follower of the Jedi path and was distrustful of Jedi Knight [[Anakin Skywalker]] because he felt that he had dangerous potential. Towards the end of the Clone Wars, he learns from Anakin that Supreme Chancellor [[Palpatine]] is the Sith Lord Darth Sidious and attempts to kill him, only to be defenestrated by the Sith Lord with the help of Anakin himself, who turns into Darth Vader.\n{{toclimit|4}}\n\n==Character conception and overview==\nSeveral early incarnations of the character who would become Mace Windu were developed in the original ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' drafts as the narrator, [[Princess Leia]]'s brother and [[Luke Skywalker]]'s friend.<ref>{{cite book|first=J.W.|last=Rinzler|title=The Making of Star Wars: The Definitive Story Behind the Original Film|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=London, England|date=2007|ISBN=978-0345494764}}</ref> Through the process of redrafting and copyediting, his character was removed from the [[Star Wars Trilogy|original trilogy]], but was reintroduced in 1994 when series creator [[George Lucas]] began writing the [[prequel trilogy]].\n\nThe character's purple [[lightsaber]] was a personal request Jackson made to Lucas as a [[quid pro quo]] for appearing in the films, as well as a way of making the character unique and easily distinguishable. Jackson's favorite color is purple, and he frequently requests that any character he plays must use an item of that color..<ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Giles|url=http://screencrush.com/star-wars-samuel-l-jackson-purple-lightsaber/|title=Samuel L. Jackson On The Hilarious Origins Of His Purple Lightsaber in 'Star Wars'|website=[[ScreenCrush]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|location=Greenwich, Connecticut|date=July 1, 2013|accessdate=November 1, 2018}}</ref> Although his weapon is not seen onscreen until ''[[Episode II \u2013 Attack of the Clones]]'', action figures released for ''[[Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'' pair Mace with a blue lightsaber.<ref>{{cite web |last=Veekhoven |first=Tim |title=The Beginning: Hasbro's Phantom Menace Toys |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/the-beginning-hasbros-phantom-menace-toys |website=StarWars.com |accessdate=October 13, 2019 |date=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n===Film===\n[[File:Star Wars and the Power of Costume July 2018 10 (Mace Windu's Jedi robes from Episode III).jpg|thumb|left|Mace Windu's Jedi robes from ''Episode III'']]\n\n====''The Phantom Menace''====\nIntroduced in ''Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace'', Windu appears as the Master of the Jedi Council.<ref name=\"Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia\" /> The maverick Jedi Master [[Qui-Gon Jinn]] comes before the Council and offers to train [[Anakin Skywalker]], believing that the boy is the Chosen One of Jedi prophecy. Windu and the other Council members decline, deeming Anakin too old and full of fear. After the corrupt Trade Federation is defeated and [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] defeats [[Sith|Sith Lord]] [[Darth Maul]], who also kills Qui-Gon, Windu realizes that the Sith have returned, and he and the Council reluctantly allow Obi-Wan to train Anakin in Qui-Gon's stead.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120915/?ref_=nv_sr_1|publisher=[[20th Century Fox]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=1999|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''Attack of the Clones''====\nIn ''[[Attack of the Clones]]'', set ten years after the previous installment, Windu initially refuses to believe that the assassination attempt on Senator [[Padm\u00e9 Amidala]] on Coruscant was authorized by former Jedi master [[Count Dooku]], the leader of a galactic Separatist movement. Having learned of Obi-Wan's whereabouts on Geonosis, Windu arrives to save Obi-Wan, Padm\u00e9 and Anakin from being executed at Dooku's order. In the ensuing battle, Windu kills bounty hunter [[Jango Fett]], the template for the [[Galactic Republic|Republic]]'s army of [[clone trooper]]s, and leads them and a cadre of Jedi to victory in a [[Battle of Geonosis|battle with Dooku's forces]]. At the end of the film, with the [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|Clone Wars]] begun, Windu resolves to keep a closer eye on the increasingly corrupt Galactic Senate.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode II: Attack of the Clones|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0121765/?ref_=fn_al_tt_2|publisher=[[20th Century Fox]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2002|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''Revenge of the Sith''====\nIn ''[[Revenge of the Sith]]'', set three years after the beginning of the Clone Wars, Windu and the other members of the Jedi Council are concerned that the Republic's Supreme Chancellor, [[Palpatine]], may not relinquish his [[emergency powers]] when the Clone Wars end. Their suspicions only grow when the Senate grants Palpatine a vote on the Jedi Council by appointing Anakin as his personal representative. The Council makes Anakin a member, but denies him the rank of Jedi Master and orders him to spy on Palpatine against the latter's will, causing Anakin's faith in the Jedi to diminish significantly. After Obi-Wan kills Separatist leader [[General Grievous]], Anakin learns Palpatine's true identity and informs Windu that Palpatine is Sith Lord Darth Sidious, the mastermind of the war. Windu and three other Jedi Masters; Kit Fisto, Agen Kolar, and Saesee Tiin attempt to arrest Palpatine, but the Sith Lord easily kills three of the Jedi, leaving Windu left to duel alone. Windu gets the upper hand and subdues Palpatine by knocking away his lightsaber and deflecting the Sith Lord's Force lightning back at him, disfiguring Palpatine's body. Anakin, needing Palpatine for the power to prevent [[Padm\u00e9 Amidala|his wife']]<nowiki/>s possible death arrives and pleads with Windu not to kill Palpatine, who feigns helplessness to implore Anakin. Windu counters that Palpatine controls the Senate and the courts, and is therefore too dangerous to be kept alive. Just as Windu is about to finish Palpatine off, Anakin intervenes on Palpatine's behalf, betraying Windu by severing his right arm and disarming him. Palpatine then tortures and defenestrates Windu with another blast of Force lightning, killing him. <!-- The Star Wars databank confirms Windu died. --> Palpatine uses Windu's death to start [[Order 66 (Star Wars)|Order 66]] and murder the vast majority of the Jedi, reducing their numbers to fewer than 100.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0121766/?ref_=tt_rec_tt|publisher=[[20th Century Fox]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2005|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''The Clone Wars''====\nWindu makes his final film appearance in the 2008 animated film ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'', set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''. He plays a supporting role as a general in the Republic's clone forces. He is voiced by Samuel L. Jackson, who portrayed the character in the live-action films.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars: The Clone Wars|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1185834/?ref_=nv_sr_2|publisher=20th Century Fox|date=2008|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''The Rise of Skywalker''====\nWindu returns as a voice cameo in the final chapter of the ''Star Wars'' sequel trilogy ''[[Star Wars: Episode IX - The Rise of Skywalker|The Rise of Skywalker]]''. During the battle between [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]] and [[Palpatine|The Emperor]], Windu's voice is heard speaking to Rey, encouraging her to rise and fight back as all of the past Jedi are with her.\n\n===Animated series===\n====''The Clone Wars'' (2008)====\nIn ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' (set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''), Mace Windu has a supporting role. As in the film, he is a general of the Republic's clone army. He is voiced by [[Terrence \"T.C.\" Carson]].\n\n===Comics===\nIn 2017, [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] released ''Star Wars: Jedi of the Republic \u2013 Mace Windu'', a 5-issue series centered around Windu during the early days of the Clone Wars. He leads a small team of Jedi on a mission to the planet Hissrich, to find out what the Separatists are doing there. During the mission, Windu's faith in the Jedi path is tested by his interactions with two new characters: AD-W4, a mercenary droid with a thirst for murdering Jedi; and Prosset Dibs, a blind Jedi Master who becomes disillusioned with the Jedi Order and turns on Windu. Ultimately, Windu ends up besting both adversaries in single combat, respectively, and his faith in the Jedi way is strengthened by the experience.\n\n===''Legends''===\nIn April 2014, most of the licensed ''Star Wars'' novels and comics produced since the originating 1977 film ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' were rebranded by Lucasfilm as ''Star Wars Legends'' and declared [[Star Wars canon|non-canon to the franchise]].<ref name=\"SW Adult\">{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/disney-publishing-worldwide-and-random-house-announce-relaunch-of-star-wars-adult-fiction-line |title=Disney and Random House announce relaunch of ''Star Wars'' Adult Fiction line |publisher=StarWars.com |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"THR Legends\">{{cite magazine|first=Graeme|last=McMilian|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lucasfilm-unveils-new-plans-star-698973 |title=Lucasfilm Unveils New Plans for ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SW Legends\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/the-legendary-star-wars-expanded-universe-turns-a-new-page |title=The Legendary ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe Turns a New Page |publisher=[[StarWars.com]] |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> Windu appears extensively in the [[Star Wars expanded universe|''Star Wars'' Legends]] of novels and comic books.\n\n====''Clone Wars'' (2003)====\nMace Windu is a supporting character in [[Genndy Tartakovsky]]'s ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'' micro-series, which is set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''. The character's likeness in the series is based on that in ''The Phantom Menace'' and ''Attack of the Clones''. In the first chapters, he defends the grasslands planet [[Dantooine]] against a large hovering \"fortress\", and over the course, he loses his lightsaber, forcing him to instead use a lethal form of unarmed combat powered by the Force. In final chapters, he and fellow Jedi Master Yoda help defend the planet [[Coruscant]] from an attack by General Grievous. In the midst of the [[Battle of Coruscant|battle]], he realizes that the attack is a ruse to distract the Jedi from Grievous's true objective: to \"kidnap\" Palpatine. Despite being too late to save the Supreme Chancellor, the Jedi Master uses the Force to crush Grievous's chest, inflicting upon the [[cyborg]] general the wheezing, [[asthma]]tic cough heard in ''Revenge of the Sith''.\n\n====Novels====\nWindu has appeared as a supporting character in Legends/Expanded Universe novels, such as ''[[Cloak of Deception]], [[Darth Maul: Shadow Hunter]], [[Rogue Planet (novel)|Rogue Planet]], [[Outbound Flight]], [[The Cestus Deception]], [[Jedi Trial]], [[Yoda: Dark Rendezvous]]'' and ''[[Labyrinth of Evil]]''.\n\n=====''Shatterpoint''=====\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Shatterpoint\n|italic title = no\n|image = \n|author = [[Matthew Stover]]\n|cover_artist = \n|country = United States\n|language = English\n|series = Canon [[Star Wars canon|C]]\n|subject =[[Star Wars]]\n|genre = [[Science fiction]]\n|publisher = [[Del Rey Books|Del Rey]] & [[Random House Audio]]\n|release_date = [[Hardcover]]: June 3, 2003<br>\n[[Paperback]]: April 23, 2004\n|pages = Hardcover: 464<br>\nPaperback: 432<br>\nAudiobook: 3h 45m 17s\n|isbn = 0-345-45573-8\n|preceded_by = Boba Fett: Hunted\n|followed_by = [[The Cestus Deception]]\n}}\n\nWindu is the central character of [[Matthew Stover]]'s 2004 novel '''''Shatterpoint''''', taking place six months after ''Attack of the Clones''. Stover based the novel on both [[Joseph Conrad]]'s novel ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'', and its loose adaptation ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''. George Lucas wrote the prologue to the novel, and Jonathan Davis reads the [[audiobook]] version.\n\nWindu's former [[Padawan (Star Wars)|Padawan]] and fellow Jedi Master [[Depa Billaba]] has been sent to Windu's homeworld, Haruun Kal, to start a revolution against the Separatist-allied government. Evidence is discovered that Billaba has fallen to the dark side of the Force. Since Windu taught her a special lightsaber combat form, he alone is sent by the Jedi Council to find her.\nAfter a fight, he puts Billaba under arrest, and calls a Republic cruiser. It is attacked by [[Vulture droid]]s and deploys gunships, which battle the droid starfighters with the assistance of clone troopers. Some of the landing craft make it to the surface, and the cruiser defeats the Separatists. Windu uses the gunships to destroy the droid fighters that followed them, then orders the clones to take out a nearby droid control station. The Separatists are forced to surrender to the Republic, and Billaba falls into a [[vegetative state|vegetative]] [[coma]]. A Republic force stays on the planet to police the unrestful local tribes.\n\nThe novel establishes that Windu has the unique talent of seeing \"shatterpoints\", or [[Fault (geology)|faultlines]] in the Force that could affect the destinies of certain individuals. Mace's shatterpoint ability also enables him to see people's weaknesses, allowing him to exploit their flaws and defeat them. It also explains that Windu is the creator and sole master of a style of lightsaber combat called Vaapad, in which the user skirts dangerously close to the dark side by enjoying the thrill of the fight. All others who attempted to master the form either gave in to the dark side or were unable to properly master the technique. Stover later referenced Windu's unique lightsaber-fighting abilities in his [[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith (novel)|novelization of ''Revenge of the Sith'']].\n\n====Comics====\nThe \"[[Star Wars: Republic#Emissaries to Malastare|Emissaries to Malastare]]\" arc of the [[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse]] comic ''[[Star Wars: Republic]]'' depicts a Jedi exercise in which the knights swap their weapons, explaining why Windu carried a blue-bladed lightsaber during the era of ''The Phantom Menace''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerard |first=Michael |title=Why Mace Windu's Lightsaber Changed From Blue To Purple In Star Wars |url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/truth-mace-windus-original-lightsaber-color/ |website=We Got This Covered |accessdate=October 13, 2019 |date=July 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandising==\nA Mace Windu action figure was added to the [[Star Wars Transformers|''Star Wars'' Transformers]] toy line in 2006. It was a remold of the toy first used for Obi-Wan Kenobi. He becomes an [[Jedi starfighter|Eta-2 Actis-class light interceptor]] starfighter with Astromech [[droid (Star Wars)|droid]] R4-M6.\n\n==Reception==\n[[IGN]] listed Mace Windu as the 27th top ''Star Wars'' character, stating that he is an important component of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/star-wars-characters/27.html|title=Top 100 Star Wars Characters: 27: Mace Windu|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[j2 Global]]|location=Los Angeles, California|accessdate=November 1, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816053002/http://www.ign.com/star-wars-characters/27.html|archivedate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction|Film}}\n*''[[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith#Novelization|Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith Novelization]] - Novelization'', 1st edition hardcover, 2005. Matthew Woodring Stover, George Lucas, {{ISBN|0-7126-8427-1}}\n*''[[Shatterpoint]]'' (novel), 1st edition, 2003. Matthew Woodring Stover, {{ISBN|0-345-45573-8}}\n*''The New Essential Guide to Characters'', 1st edition, 2002. Daniel Wallace, Michael Sutfin, {{ISBN|0-345-44900-2}}\n*''Star Wars: The Phantom Menace: The Visual Dictionary'', hardcover, 1999. David West Reynolds, {{ISBN|0-7894-4701-0}}\n*''Star Wars: Attack of the Clones: The Visual Dictionary'', hardcover, 2002. David West Reynolds, {{ISBN|0-7894-8588-5}}\n*''Revised Core Rulebook (Star Wars Roleplaying Game)'', 1st edition, 2002. Bill Slavicsek, Andy Collins, J.D. Wiker, Steve Sansweet, {{ISBN|0-7869-2876-X}}\n*''Star Wars Roleplaying Game: Power of the Jedi Sourcebook'', hardcover, 2002. Michael Mikaelian, Jeff Grubb, Owen K.C. Stephens, James Maliszewski, {{ISBN|0-7869-2781-X}}\n*''Star Wars Galaxy Guide 7: Mos Eisley'', softcover, 1993. Martin Wixted, {{ISBN|0-87431-187-X}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Star Wars Databank |subject=mace-windu|text=Mace Windu}}\n* {{Wookieepedia|Mace Windu}}\n\n{{Star Wars universe}}\n{{Star Wars: The Clone Wars}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1=1990s |portal3=Speculative fiction|portal31=Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Windu, Mace}}\n[[Category:Characters created by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Black characters in films]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1999]]\n[[Category:Fictional generals]]\n[[Category:Fictional knights]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional telekinetics]]\n[[Category:Fictional war veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional murdered people in film]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Star Wars comics characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars literary characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Skywalker Saga characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars television characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars video game characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Jedi characters]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|Windu|the cycle of 8 lunar years|Javanese calendar}}\n{{short description|Fictional character in Star Wars}}\n{{Infobox character\n| name               = Mace Windu\n| image              = Mace Windu.png\n| caption            = Samuel L. Jackson as Mace Windu\n| series             = [[Star Wars]]\n| first              = ''[[Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace|The Phantom Menace]]'' (1999)\n| last               = ''[[Star Wars: The Rise of Skywalker|The Rise of Skywalker]]'' (2019)\n| creator            = [[George Lucas]]\n| occupation         = [[Jedi]]\n| title              = {{plainlist|\n* Jedi (former)\n* Jedi Knight (former)\n* Jedi Master\n* Republic General (during the Clone Wars)\n}}\n| species            = Human\n| gender             = Male\n| lbl21              = Homeworld\n| data21             = [[List of Star Wars planets and moons#Haruun Kal|Haruun Kal]]\n| affiliation        = [[Jedi|Jedi Order]]<br>[[Galactic Republic]]\n| portrayer          = [[Samuel L. Jackson]]\n| voice              = {{unbulleted list|[[Terrence C. Carson]] <br> ([[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2002 video game)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' (video game)]], ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'', [[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith (video game)|''Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith'' (video game)]], ''[[Star Wars: Battlefront II (2005 video game)|Star Wars: Battlefront II]]'', ''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' (TV series), ''[[Star Wars Battlefront: Elite Squadron]]'', ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars: Republic Heroes]]'', ''[[Kinect Star Wars]]'' and ''[[Disney Infinity 3.0]]'')|Samuel L. Jackson <br>([[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|''Star Wars: The Clone Wars'' (film)]], ''[[Lego Star Wars III: The Clone Wars]]'' and ''Episode IX'')|[[Kevin Michael Richardson]]<br> (''[[Star Wars Episode I: Jedi Power Battles|Jedi Power Battles]]'', ''[[Star Wars: Obi-Wan]]'' and ''[[Star Wars: Jedi Starfighter|Jedi Starfighter]]'')|[[Donald Glover]] <br>(''[[Robot Chicken: Star Wars Episode III|Robot Chicken]]'')|[[Adrian Holmes]] <br>(''[[Lego Star Wars: The Yoda Chronicles|The Yoda Chronicles]]'' and ''[[Lego Star Wars: Droid Tales|Droid Tales]]'')}}\n}}\n\n'''Mace Windu'''  is a [[fictional character]] in the ''[[Star Wars]]'' franchise, portrayed by [[actor]] [[Samuel L. Jackson]] in the [[Star Wars prequel trilogy|prequel films]] and voiced by Jackson in the animated film ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' while voice actor [[Terrence C. Carson]] voices him in other projects, such as [[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|''The Clone Wars'' television series]]. He is a human male, a [[Jedi master]] on the [[Jedi Council|High Council]] and one of the last members of the order's upper echelons before the [[Galactic Republic]]'s fall. Despite the [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|Clone Wars]] causing him to question his most firmly held beliefs,<ref name=\"Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia\">{{cite book|first1=Stephen J.|last1=Sansweet|first2=Pablo|last2=Hidalgo|first3=Bob|last3=Vitas|title=The Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia|publisher=[[LucasBooks]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2008|ISBN= 978-0345477637}}</ref> he is a staunch follower of the Jedi path and was distrustful of Jedi Knight [[Anakin Skywalker]] because he felt that he had dangerous potential. Towards the end of the Clone Wars, he learns from Anakin that Supreme Chancellor [[Palpatine]] is the Sith Lord Darth Sidious and attempts to kill him, only to be defenestrated by the Sith Lord with the help of Anakin himself, who turns into Darth Vader.\n{{toclimit|4}}\n\n==Character conception and overview==\nSeveral early incarnations of the character who would become Mace Windu were developed in the original ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' drafts as the narrator, [[Princess Leia]]'s brother and [[Luke Skywalker]]'s friend.<ref>{{cite book|first=J.W.|last=Rinzler|title=The Making of Star Wars: The Definitive Story Behind the Original Film|publisher=[[Del Rey Books]]|location=London, England|date=2007|ISBN=978-0345494764}}</ref> Through the process of redrafting and copyediting, his character was removed from the [[Star Wars Trilogy|original trilogy]], but was reintroduced in 1994 when series creator [[George Lucas]] began writing the [[prequel trilogy]].\n\nThe character's purple [[lightsaber]] was a personal request Jackson made to Lucas as a [[quid pro quo]] for appearing in the films, as well as a way of making the character unique and easily distinguishable. Jackson's favorite color is purple, and he frequently requests that any character he plays must use an item of that color..<ref>{{cite web|first=Jeff|last=Giles|url=http://screencrush.com/star-wars-samuel-l-jackson-purple-lightsaber/|title=Samuel L. Jackson On The Hilarious Origins Of His Purple Lightsaber in 'Star Wars'|website=[[ScreenCrush]]|publisher=[[Townsquare Media]]|location=Greenwich, Connecticut|date=July 1, 2013|accessdate=November 1, 2018}}</ref> Although his weapon is not seen onscreen until ''[[Episode II \u2013 Attack of the Clones]]'', action figures released for ''[[Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace]]'' pair Mace with a blue lightsaber.<ref>{{cite web |last=Veekhoven |first=Tim |title=The Beginning: Hasbro's Phantom Menace Toys |url=https://www.starwars.com/news/the-beginning-hasbros-phantom-menace-toys |website=StarWars.com |accessdate=October 13, 2019 |date=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Appearances==\n===Film===\n[[File:Star Wars and the Power of Costume July 2018 10 (Mace Windu's Jedi robes from Episode III).jpg|thumb|left|Mace Windu's Jedi robes from ''Episode III'']]\n\n====''The Phantom Menace''====\nIntroduced in ''Star Wars: Episode I \u2013 The Phantom Menace'', Windu appears as the Master of the Jedi Council.<ref name=\"Complete Star Wars Encyclopedia\" /> The maverick Jedi Master [[Qui-Gon Jinn]] comes before the Council and offers to train [[Anakin Skywalker]], believing that the boy is the Chosen One of Jedi prophecy. Windu and the other Council members decline, deeming Anakin too old and full of fear. After the corrupt Trade Federation is defeated and [[Obi-Wan Kenobi]] defeats [[Sith|Sith Lord]] [[Darth Maul]], who also kills Qui-Gon, Windu realizes that the Sith have returned, and he and the Council reluctantly allow Obi-Wan to train Anakin in Qui-Gon's stead.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120915/?ref_=nv_sr_1|publisher=[[20th Century Fox]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=1999|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''Attack of the Clones''====\nIn ''[[Attack of the Clones]]'', set ten years after the previous installment, Windu initially refuses to believe that the assassination attempt on Senator [[Padm\u00e9 Amidala]] on Coruscant was authorized by former Jedi master [[Count Dooku]], the leader of a galactic Separatist movement. Having learned of Obi-Wan's whereabouts on Geonosis, Windu arrives to save Obi-Wan, Padm\u00e9 and Anakin from being executed at Dooku's order. In the ensuing battle, Windu kills bounty hunter [[Jango Fett]], the template for the [[Galactic Republic|Republic]]'s army of [[clone trooper]]s, and leads them and a cadre of Jedi to victory in a [[Battle of Geonosis|battle with Dooku's forces]]. At the end of the film, with the [[Clone Wars (Star Wars)|Clone Wars]] begun, Windu resolves to keep a closer eye on the increasingly corrupt Galactic Senate.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode II: Attack of the Clones|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0121765/?ref_=fn_al_tt_2|publisher=[[20th Century Fox]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2002|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''Revenge of the Sith''====\nIn ''[[Revenge of the Sith]]'', set three years after the beginning of the Clone Wars, Windu and the other members of the Jedi Council are concerned that the Republic's Supreme Chancellor, [[Palpatine]], may not relinquish his [[emergency powers]] when the Clone Wars end. Their suspicions only grow when the Senate grants Palpatine a vote on the Jedi Council by appointing Anakin as his personal representative. The Council makes Anakin a member, but denies him the rank of Jedi Master and orders him to spy on Palpatine against the latter's will, causing Anakin's faith in the Jedi to diminish significantly. After Obi-Wan kills Separatist leader [[General Grievous]], Anakin learns Palpatine's true identity and informs Windu that Palpatine is Sith Lord Darth Sidious, the mastermind of the war. Windu and three other Jedi Masters; Kit Fisto, Agen Kolar, and Saesee Tiin attempt to arrest Palpatine, but the Sith Lord easily kills three of the Jedi, leaving Windu left to duel alone. Windu gets the upper hand and subdues Palpatine by knocking away his lightsaber and deflecting the Sith Lord's Force lightning back at him, disfiguring Palpatine's body. Anakin, needing Palpatine for the power to prevent [[Padm\u00e9 Amidala|his wife']]<nowiki/>s possible death arrives and pleads with Windu not to kill Palpatine, who feigns helplessness to implore Anakin. Windu counters that Palpatine controls the Senate and the courts, and is therefore too dangerous to be kept alive. Just as Windu is about to finish Palpatine off, Anakin intervenes on Palpatine's behalf, betraying Windu by severing his right arm and disarming him. Palpatine then tortures and kills Windu with another blast of Force lightning, killing him. <!-- The Star Wars databank confirms Windu died. --> Palpatine uses Windu's death to start [[Order 66 (Star Wars)|Order 66]] and murder the vast majority of the Jedi, reducing their numbers to fewer than 100.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0121766/?ref_=tt_rec_tt|publisher=[[20th Century Fox]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=2005|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''The Clone Wars''====\nWindu makes his final film appearance in the 2008 animated film ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (film)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'', set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''. He plays a supporting role as a general in the Republic's clone forces. He is voiced by Samuel L. Jackson, who portrayed the character in the live-action films.<ref>{{cite AV media|title=Star Wars: The Clone Wars|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1185834/?ref_=nv_sr_2|publisher=20th Century Fox|date=2008|format=DVD}}</ref>\n\n====''The Rise of Skywalker''====\nWindu returns as a voice cameo in the final chapter of the ''Star Wars'' sequel trilogy ''[[Star Wars: Episode IX - The Rise of Skywalker|The Rise of Skywalker]]''. During the battle between [[Rey (Star Wars)|Rey]] and [[Palpatine|The Emperor]], Windu's voice is heard speaking to Rey, encouraging her to rise and fight back as all of the past Jedi are with her.\n\n===Animated series===\n====''The Clone Wars'' (2008)====\nIn ''[[Star Wars: The Clone Wars (2008 TV series)|Star Wars: The Clone Wars]]'' (set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''), Mace Windu has a supporting role. As in the film, he is a general of the Republic's clone army. He is voiced by [[Terrence \"T.C.\" Carson]].\n\n===Comics===\nIn 2017, [[Marvel Comics|Marvel]] released ''Star Wars: Jedi of the Republic \u2013 Mace Windu'', a 5-issue series centered around Windu during the early days of the Clone Wars. He leads a small team of Jedi on a mission to the planet Hissrich, to find out what the Separatists are doing there. During the mission, Windu's faith in the Jedi path is tested by his interactions with two new characters: AD-W4, a mercenary droid with a thirst for murdering Jedi; and Prosset Dibs, a blind Jedi Master who becomes disillusioned with the Jedi Order and turns on Windu. Ultimately, Windu ends up besting both adversaries in single combat, respectively, and his faith in the Jedi way is strengthened by the experience.\n\n===''Legends''===\nIn April 2014, most of the licensed ''Star Wars'' novels and comics produced since the originating 1977 film ''[[Star Wars (film)|Star Wars]]'' were rebranded by Lucasfilm as ''Star Wars Legends'' and declared [[Star Wars canon|non-canon to the franchise]].<ref name=\"SW Adult\">{{cite web|url=https://www.starwars.com/news/disney-publishing-worldwide-and-random-house-announce-relaunch-of-star-wars-adult-fiction-line |title=Disney and Random House announce relaunch of ''Star Wars'' Adult Fiction line |publisher=StarWars.com |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"THR Legends\">{{cite magazine|first=Graeme|last=McMilian|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/lucasfilm-unveils-new-plans-star-698973 |title=Lucasfilm Unveils New Plans for ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe |magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"SW Legends\">{{cite web|url=http://www.starwars.com/news/the-legendary-star-wars-expanded-universe-turns-a-new-page |title=The Legendary ''Star Wars'' Expanded Universe Turns a New Page |publisher=[[StarWars.com]] |date=April 25, 2014 |accessdate=May 26, 2016}}</ref> Windu appears extensively in the [[Star Wars expanded universe|''Star Wars'' Legends]] of novels and comic books.\n\n====''Clone Wars'' (2003)====\nMace Windu is a supporting character in [[Genndy Tartakovsky]]'s ''[[Star Wars: Clone Wars (2003 TV series)|Star Wars: Clone Wars]]'' micro-series, which is set between ''Attack of the Clones'' and ''Revenge of the Sith''. The character's likeness in the series is based on that in ''The Phantom Menace'' and ''Attack of the Clones''. In the first chapters, he defends the grasslands planet [[Dantooine]] against a large hovering \"fortress\", and over the course, he loses his lightsaber, forcing him to instead use a lethal form of unarmed combat powered by the Force. In final chapters, he and fellow Jedi Master Yoda help defend the planet [[Coruscant]] from an attack by General Grievous. In the midst of the [[Battle of Coruscant|battle]], he realizes that the attack is a ruse to distract the Jedi from Grievous's true objective: to \"kidnap\" Palpatine. Despite being too late to save the Supreme Chancellor, the Jedi Master uses the Force to crush Grievous's chest, inflicting upon the [[cyborg]] general the wheezing, [[asthma]]tic cough heard in ''Revenge of the Sith''.\n\n====Novels====\nWindu has appeared as a supporting character in Legends/Expanded Universe novels, such as ''[[Cloak of Deception]], [[Darth Maul: Shadow Hunter]], [[Rogue Planet (novel)|Rogue Planet]], [[Outbound Flight]], [[The Cestus Deception]], [[Jedi Trial]], [[Yoda: Dark Rendezvous]]'' and ''[[Labyrinth of Evil]]''.\n\n=====''Shatterpoint''=====\n{{Infobox book\n|name = Shatterpoint\n|italic title = no\n|image = \n|author = [[Matthew Stover]]\n|cover_artist = \n|country = United States\n|language = English\n|series = Canon [[Star Wars canon|C]]\n|subject =[[Star Wars]]\n|genre = [[Science fiction]]\n|publisher = [[Del Rey Books|Del Rey]] & [[Random House Audio]]\n|release_date = [[Hardcover]]: June 3, 2003<br>\n[[Paperback]]: April 23, 2004\n|pages = Hardcover: 464<br>\nPaperback: 432<br>\nAudiobook: 3h 45m 17s\n|isbn = 0-345-45573-8\n|preceded_by = Boba Fett: Hunted\n|followed_by = [[The Cestus Deception]]\n}}\n\nWindu is the central character of [[Matthew Stover]]'s 2004 novel '''''Shatterpoint''''', taking place six months after ''Attack of the Clones''. Stover based the novel on both [[Joseph Conrad]]'s novel ''[[Heart of Darkness]]'', and its loose adaptation ''[[Apocalypse Now]]''. George Lucas wrote the prologue to the novel, and Jonathan Davis reads the [[audiobook]] version.\n\nWindu's former [[Padawan (Star Wars)|Padawan]] and fellow Jedi Master [[Depa Billaba]] has been sent to Windu's homeworld, Haruun Kal, to start a revolution against the Separatist-allied government. Evidence is discovered that Billaba has fallen to the dark side of the Force. Since Windu taught her a special lightsaber combat form, he alone is sent by the Jedi Council to find her.\nAfter a fight, he puts Billaba under arrest, and calls a Republic cruiser. It is attacked by [[Vulture droid]]s and deploys gunships, which battle the droid starfighters with the assistance of clone troopers. Some of the landing craft make it to the surface, and the cruiser defeats the Separatists. Windu uses the gunships to destroy the droid fighters that followed them, then orders the clones to take out a nearby droid control station. The Separatists are forced to surrender to the Republic, and Billaba falls into a [[vegetative state|vegetative]] [[coma]]. A Republic force stays on the planet to police the unrestful local tribes.\n\nThe novel establishes that Windu has the unique talent of seeing \"shatterpoints\", or [[Fault (geology)|faultlines]] in the Force that could affect the destinies of certain individuals. Mace's shatterpoint ability also enables him to see people's weaknesses, allowing him to exploit their flaws and defeat them. It also explains that Windu is the creator and sole master of a style of lightsaber combat called Vaapad, in which the user skirts dangerously close to the dark side by enjoying the thrill of the fight. All others who attempted to master the form either gave in to the dark side or were unable to properly master the technique. Stover later referenced Windu's unique lightsaber-fighting abilities in his [[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith (novel)|novelization of ''Revenge of the Sith'']].\n\n====Comics====\nThe \"[[Star Wars: Republic#Emissaries to Malastare|Emissaries to Malastare]]\" arc of the [[Dark Horse Comics|Dark Horse]] comic ''[[Star Wars: Republic]]'' depicts a Jedi exercise in which the knights swap their weapons, explaining why Windu carried a blue-bladed lightsaber during the era of ''The Phantom Menace''.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gerard |first=Michael |title=Why Mace Windu's Lightsaber Changed From Blue To Purple In Star Wars |url=https://wegotthiscovered.com/movies/truth-mace-windus-original-lightsaber-color/ |website=We Got This Covered |accessdate=October 13, 2019 |date=July 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Merchandising==\nA Mace Windu action figure was added to the [[Star Wars Transformers|''Star Wars'' Transformers]] toy line in 2006. It was a remold of the toy first used for Obi-Wan Kenobi. He becomes an [[Jedi starfighter|Eta-2 Actis-class light interceptor]] starfighter with Astromech [[droid (Star Wars)|droid]] R4-M6.\n\n==Reception==\n[[IGN]] listed Mace Windu as the 27th top ''Star Wars'' character, stating that he is an important component of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/star-wars-characters/27.html|title=Top 100 Star Wars Characters: 27: Mace Windu|website=[[IGN]]|publisher=[[j2 Global]]|location=Los Angeles, California|accessdate=November 1, 2018|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100816053002/http://www.ign.com/star-wars-characters/27.html|archivedate=August 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Portal|Speculative fiction|Film}}\n*''[[Star Wars: Episode III \u2013 Revenge of the Sith#Novelization|Star Wars Episode III: Revenge of the Sith Novelization]] - Novelization'', 1st edition hardcover, 2005. Matthew Woodring Stover, George Lucas, {{ISBN|0-7126-8427-1}}\n*''[[Shatterpoint]]'' (novel), 1st edition, 2003. Matthew Woodring Stover, {{ISBN|0-345-45573-8}}\n*''The New Essential Guide to Characters'', 1st edition, 2002. Daniel Wallace, Michael Sutfin, {{ISBN|0-345-44900-2}}\n*''Star Wars: The Phantom Menace: The Visual Dictionary'', hardcover, 1999. David West Reynolds, {{ISBN|0-7894-4701-0}}\n*''Star Wars: Attack of the Clones: The Visual Dictionary'', hardcover, 2002. David West Reynolds, {{ISBN|0-7894-8588-5}}\n*''Revised Core Rulebook (Star Wars Roleplaying Game)'', 1st edition, 2002. Bill Slavicsek, Andy Collins, J.D. Wiker, Steve Sansweet, {{ISBN|0-7869-2876-X}}\n*''Star Wars Roleplaying Game: Power of the Jedi Sourcebook'', hardcover, 2002. Michael Mikaelian, Jeff Grubb, Owen K.C. Stephens, James Maliszewski, {{ISBN|0-7869-2781-X}}\n*''Star Wars Galaxy Guide 7: Mos Eisley'', softcover, 1993. Martin Wixted, {{ISBN|0-87431-187-X}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Star Wars Databank |subject=mace-windu|text=Mace Windu}}\n* {{Wookieepedia|Mace Windu}}\n\n{{Star Wars universe}}\n{{Star Wars: The Clone Wars}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1=1990s |portal3=Speculative fiction|portal31=Film}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Windu, Mace}}\n[[Category:Characters created by George Lucas]]\n[[Category:Black characters in films]]\n[[Category:Film characters introduced in 1999]]\n[[Category:Fictional generals]]\n[[Category:Fictional knights]]\n[[Category:Fictional swordsmen]]\n[[Category:Fictional telekinetics]]\n[[Category:Fictional war veterans]]\n[[Category:Fictional murdered people in film]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Male characters in film]]\n[[Category:Male characters in television]]\n[[Category:Star Wars comics characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars literary characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Skywalker Saga characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars television characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars video game characters]]\n[[Category:Star Wars Jedi characters]]\n", "name_user": "UpdateNerd", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRevenge of the Sith:ce", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mace_Windu"}
